# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: absolute-monarchy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:absolute-monarchy/1814-in-norway] 1814 has historically been considered the most important year in the history of Norway.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1814-in-norway] Sovereignty was transferred from the King of Denmark to the King of Sweden.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1814-in-norway] The Constitution of Norway was signed at Eidsvoll on May 17, later to be designated and celebrated as Norwegian Constitution Day.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1814-in-norway] For a detailed account of the events surrounding the re-formation of the country in modern times, see the article **Kingdom of Norway (1814)**.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1848-in-denmark] Events from the year **1848 in Denmark**.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The **1911 Revolution**, also known as the **Xinhai Revolution** or **Hsinhai Revolution**, culminated in the end of China's last imperial dynasty, the Qing dynasty, and led to the establishment of the Republic of China (ROC).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolution was the culmination of a decade of agitation, revolts, and uprisings.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Its success marked the end of Chinese monarchy, the 267-year reign of the Qing, over two millennia of imperial rule in China, and the beginning of China's early republican era.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing had long struggled to reform the government and resist foreign aggression, but conservatives in the Qing court opposed the program of reforms after 1900 as too radical and reformers considered it too slow.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Several factions, including underground anti-Qing groups, revolutionaries in exile, reformers who wanted to save the monarchy by modernizing it, and activists across the country debated how or whether to overthrow the Qing dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The flashpoint came on 10 October 1911 with the Wuchang Uprising, an armed rebellion by members of the New Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Similar revolts then broke out spontaneously around the country, and revolutionaries in every province renounced the Qing dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 1 November 1911, the Qing court appointed Yuan Shikai (leader of the Beiyang Army) as prime minister, and he began negotiations with the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In Nanjing, revolutionary forces created a provisional coalition government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 1 January 1912, the Advisory Council declared the establishment of the Republic of China, with Sun Yat-sen, leader of the Tongmenghui, as President of the Republic of China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A brief civil war between the North and the South ended in compromise.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun resigned in favor of Yuan, who would become president of the new national government if he could secure the abdication of the Qing emperor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The edict of abdication of the six-year-old Xuantong Emperor was promulgated on 12 February 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Yuan was sworn in as president on 10 March 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In December 1915, Yuan restored the monarchy and proclaimed himself the Hongxian Emperor, but the move was met with strong opposition by the population and the Army, leading to his abdication in March 1916 and the Republic's reinstatement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Yuan's failure to consolidate a legitimate central government before his death in June 1916 led to decades of political division and warlordism, including an attempt at imperial restoration of the Qing dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The name "Xinhai Revolution" derives from the traditional Chinese calendar, where "Xinhai" (辛亥) is the label corresponding to 1911 according to the sexagenary cycle.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The governments of both Taiwan and China consider themselves the legitimate successors to the 1911 Revolution and honor the ideals of the revolution, including nationalism, republicanism, modernization of China, and national unity.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] 10 October is the National Day of the Republic of China on Taiwan, and the Anniversary of the 1911 Revolution in China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the 1911 Revolution, Liang became Minister of Justice of the Republic of China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After suffering its first defeat by the West in the First Opium War in 1842, a conservative court culture constrained efforts to reform and did not want to cede authority to local officials.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After its defeat in the Second Opium War in 1860, the Qing began efforts to modernize by adopting Western technologies through the Self-Strengthening Movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After a generation of relative success in importing Western naval and weapons technology, the Chinese defeat to Imperial Japan in the First Sino-Japanese War in 1895 was all the more humiliating and convinced many of the need for institutional change.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The court established the New Army under Yuan Shikai, and many concluded that Chinese society also needed to be modernized if technological and commercial advancements were to succeed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1898, the Guangxu Emperor turned to reformers like Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao, who offered a program that was inspired in large part by the reforms in Japan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They proposed basic reform in education, military, and economy in the so-called Hundred Days' Reform.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The reform was abruptly canceled by a conservative coup, led by Empress Dowager Cixi.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Emperor was put under house arrest in June 1898, where he remained until his death in 1908.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The reformers Kang and Liang exiled themselves to avoid being executed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Empress Dowager controlled policy until her death in 1908, with support from officials such as Yuan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Attacks on foreigners and Chinese Christians in the Boxer Rebellion by Chinese nationalists, which was encouraged by the Empress Dowager, prompted another foreign invasion of Beijing in 1900.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the Allies imposed a punitive settlement, the Qing court carried out basic fiscal and administrative reforms, including local and provincial elections.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The moves did not secure trust or wide support among political activists.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many of them like Zou Rong felt strong anti-Manchu prejudice and blamed the Qing for China's troubles.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Kang Youwei and Liang Qichao formed the Emperor Protection Society in an attempt to restore the emperor, but others, such as Sun Yat-sen organized revolutionary groups to overthrow the dynasty, rather than reform it.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They could operate only in secret societies and underground organizations, in foreign concessions, or exile overseas but created a following among overseas Chinese in North America, Southeast Asia and within China, even in the new armies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen believed that China needed to transition from an absolute monarchy to a democratic republic and believed that a revolution was the only way to modernize China and defend its sovereignty from Western colonial powers and Japan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Chinese famine of 1906–1907 was also a major contributor to the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Following the death of the Guangxu Emperor and Cixi in 1908, the throne was inherited by the two-year-old Xuantong Emperor, with Prince Chun as a regent.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The prince continued the reform path of Cixi, but conservative Manchu elements in the court opposed it, which caused further support for revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many revolutionaries and groups wanted to overthrow the Qing government to re-establish the Han-led government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The earliest revolutionary organizations were founded outside of China, such as Yeung Ku-wan's Furen Literary Society, which was created in British Hong Kong in 1890.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] There were 15 members, including Tse Tsan-tai, who made political satire such as "The Situation in the Far East", one of the first manhua, and who later became one of the core founders of the *South China Morning Post*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun's Revive China Society was established in Honolulu in 1894, the main purpose being raising funds for revolutions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Huaxinghui (China Revival Society) was founded in 1904 by the notables Huang Xing, Zhang Shizhao, Chen Tianhua, Sun Yat-sen, Song Jiaoren, and 100 others.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Guangfuhui (Restoration Society) was also founded in 1904 in Shanghai, by Cai Yuanpei.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Other notable members included Zhang Binglin and Tao Chengzhang.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Despite professing the anti-Qing cause, the Guangfuhui was highly critical of Sun Yat-sen.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] One of the most famous female revolutionaries was Qiu Jin, who fought for women's rights and was also from the Guangfuhui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Gelaohui (Elder Brother Society) was another group, with Zhu De, Wu Yuzhang, Liu Zhidan (劉志丹) and He Long.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionary group would eventually develop a strong link with the later Chinese Communist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Tiandihui (Heaven and Earth Society) were groups of secretive, anti-Manchu fraternities provided the vital manpower, military networks and localized uprisings that ultimately toppled the Qing Dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Originally formed in the 17th century as a network to oppose the ruling Qing and restore the Han Chinese Ming dynasty, the Tiandihui operated on blood oaths and the rallying cry "Oppose Qing, restore Ming" (Fan Qing Fu Ming).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] By the early 20th century, the anti-Qing sentiment was easily adapted by Republican revolutionaries into a modern nationalist movement aimed at stripping the Manchus of power and returning China to the Han majority.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen recognized that modern, reform-minded intellectuals lacked the military might or broad grassroots reach required to fight the imperial state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] To bridge this gap, he actively courted secret societies and even joined the Tiandihui's overseas branch in Hawaii (the Hongmen).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] He utilized these deeply established, underground networks to smuggle weapons, raise funds from the overseas Chinese diaspora and recruit guerrilla fighters for his early, abortive uprisings in southern China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen successfully united the Revive China Society, the Huaxinghui, and the Guangfuhui and established the unified Tongmenghui (United League) in August 1905 in Tokyo.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It had loose organizations distributed across and outside China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen was the leader of the unified group.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Other revolutionaries who worked with the Tongmenghui include Wang Jingwei and Hu Hanmin.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] When the Tongmenghui was established, more than 90% of the Tongmenghui members were between 17 and 26 years old.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some of the work in the era includes manhua publications such as the *Journal of Current Pictorial*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In February 1906, Rizhihui (日知會) also had many revolutionaries, including Sun Wu (孫武), Zhang Nanxian (張難先), He Jiwei and Feng Mumin.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A nucleus of attendees at the conference evolved into the Tongmenghui's establishment in Hubei.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In July 1907, several members of the Tongmenghui in Tokyo advocated a revolution in the area of the Yangtze.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Liu Quiyi (劉揆一), Jiao Dafeng (焦達峰), Zhang Boxiang (張伯祥) and Sun Wu (孫武) established the Gongjinhui (共進會).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In January 1911, the revolutionary group Zhengwu Xueshe (振武學社) was renamed as Wenxueshe (Literary Society) (文學社).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Jiang Yiwu (蔣翊武) was chosen as the leader.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Both organizations would play a major role during the Wuchang Uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many young revolutionaries supported anarchism in China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In Tokyo, Liu Shipei proposed to overthrow the Manchus and return to Chinese classical values.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In Paris, well-connected young intellectuals, Li Shizhen, Wu Zhihui and Zhang Renjie, agreed with Sun's revolutionary program and joined the Tongmenghui but argued that simply replacing one government with another would not be progress.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They believed that fundamental cultural change and a revolution in family, gender, and social values would remove the need for government and coercion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Zhang Ji and Wang Jingwei were among the anarchists, who defended assassination and terrorism as means to awaken the people to revolution, but others insisted that education was the only justifiable strategy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Important anarchists included Cai Yuanpei.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Zhang Renjie gave Sun major financial help.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many of the anarchists would later assume high positions in the Kuomintang.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many revolutionaries promoted anti-Qing and anti-Manchu sentiments and revived memories of conflict between the minority Manchu and the majority Han Chinese from the late Ming dynasty (1368–1644).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Leading intellectuals were influenced by books that had survived from the final years of the Ming dynasty, the last Han Chinese dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1904, Sun Yat-sen announced that his organization's goal was "to expel the Tatar barbarians, to revive Zhonghua, establish a republic, and distribute land equally among the people." (驅除韃虜, 恢復中華, 創立民國, 平均地權).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many underground groups promoted the ideas of "resist Qing and restore the Ming" (反清復明), which had been around since the days of the Taiping Rebellion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Others, such as Zhang Binglin, spread calls to "slay the Manchus" (興漢滅胡) and the concept of "Anti-Manchuism" (排滿主義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many groups supported the 1911 Revolution, including students and intellectuals returning from abroad, participants of revolutionary organizations, overseas Chinese, soldiers of the new army, local gentry, and farmers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Assistance from the overseas Chinese was important in the 1911 Revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1894, the first year of the Revive China Society, the first meeting ever held by the group was held in the home of Ho Fon, an overseas Chinese who was the leader of the first Chinese Church of Christ.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The overseas Chinese supported and actively participated in funding revolutionary activities, especially the Southeast Asian Chinese of British Malaya.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many of those groups were reorganized by Sun, who was referred to as the "father of the Chinese revolution".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing government established new schools and encouraged students to study abroad as part of the Self-Strengthening movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many young people attended the new schools or went abroad to study in places like Japan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A new progressive class of intellectuals emerged from those students and contributed immensely to the 1911 Revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Besides Sun, key figures in the revolution, such as Huang Xing, Song Jiaoren, Hu Hanmin, Liao Zhongkai, Zhu Zhixin, and Wang Jingwei were all Chinese students in Japan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some were young students like Zou Rong, known for writing *Revolutionary Army*, a book in which he supported the extermination of the Manchus for the 260 years of oppression, sorrow, cruelty, and tyranny and creating new revolutionary Han figures.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Before 1908, revolutionaries focused on coordinating those organizations in preparation for uprisings they would launch; the groups would provide most of the manpower needed to overthrow the Qing dynasty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the 1911 Revolution, Sun recalled the days of recruiting support for the revolution and said, "The literati were deeply into the search for honors and profits, so they were regarded as having only secondary importance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The gentry's strength in local politics became apparent.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] From December 1908, the Qing government created some apparatus to allow the gentry and businessmen to participate in politics.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Those middle-class people were originally supporters of constitutionalism.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] However, they became disenchanted when the Qing government created a cabinet with Prince Qing as prime minister.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] By early 1911, an experimental cabinet had thirteen members, nine of whom were Manchus selected from the imperial family.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Besides Chinese and overseas Chinese, some supporters and participants of the 1911 Revolution were foreigners, and the Japanese were the most active group.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some Japanese even became members of the Tongmenghui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Miyazaki Touten was the closest Japanese supporter; others included Heiyama Shu and Ryōhei Uchida.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Homer Lea, an American, who became Sun Yat-sen's closest foreign advisor in 1910, supported his military ambitions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Mulkern also took part in the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some foreigners, such as the English explorer Arthur de Carle Sowerby, led expeditions to rescue foreign missionaries in 1911 and 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The far right-wing Japanese ultra-nationalist Black Dragon Society supported Sun Yat-sen's activities against the Manchus and believed that overthrowing the Qing would help the Japanese take over the Manchu homeland and that Han Chinese would not oppose the takeover.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Toyama believed that the Japanese could easily take over Manchuria and that Sun Yat-sen and other anti-Qing revolutionaries would not resist and help the Japanese take over and enlarge the opium trade in China, while the Qing was trying to destroy the opium trade.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Japanese Black Dragons supported Sun Yat-sen and anti-Manchu revolutionaries until the Qing collapsed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The far right-wing Japanese ultranationalist Gen'yōsha leader Tōyama Mitsuru supported anti-Manchu and anti-Qing revolutionary activities, including those organized by Sun and supported Japanese taking over Manchuria.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The anti-Qing Tongmenghui was founded and based in exile in Japan, where many anti-Qing revolutionaries gathered.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Japanese had been trying to unite anti-Manchu groups made out of Han people to take down the Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Japanese helped Sun Yat-sen unite all anti-Qing, anti-Manchu revolutionary groups together, and there were Japanese like Tōten Miyazaki in of the anti-Manchu Tongmenghui revolutionary alliance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Black Dragon Society hosted the Tongmenghui in its first meeting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Black Dragon Society had very intimate, long term and influential relations with Sun Yat-sen, who sometimes passed himself off as Japanese.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] According to an American military historian, Japanese military officers were part of the Black Dragon Society.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Yakuza and Black Dragon Society helped arrange in Tokyo for Sun Yat-sen to hold the first Kuomintang meetings, and were hoping to flood China with opium and overthrow the Qing and deceive the Chinese into overthrowing the Qing to Japan's benefit.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the revolution was successful, the Japanese Black Dragons started infiltrating China and spreading opium.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1932, the Black Dragons pushed for the takeover of Manchuria by Japan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen was married to a Japanese woman, Kaoru Otsuki.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The New Army was formed in 1901, after the Qing defeat in the First Sino-Japanese War, and was launched by a decree from eight provinces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The New Army troops were by far the best trained and equipped.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Recruits were of a higher quality than the old army and received regular promotions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1908, the revolutionaries began to shift their call to the new armies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen and the revolutionaries infiltrated the New Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Most of the central foci of the uprisings were connected with the Tongmenghui and Sun Yat-sen, including subgroups.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some uprisings involved groups that never merged with the Tongmenghui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen may have participated in 8–10 uprisings; all uprisings failed before the Wuchang Uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In the spring of 1895, the Revive China Society, based in Hong Kong, planned the First Guangzhou Uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Lu Haodong was tasked with designing the revolutionaries' Blue Sky with a White Sun flag.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 26 October 1895, Yeung Ku-wan and Sun Yat-sen led Zheng Shiliang and Lu Haodong to Guangzhou, preparing to capture Guangzhou in one strike.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] However, the details of their plans were leaked to the Qing government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The government began to arrest revolutionaries, including Lu Haodong, who was later executed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The First Guangzhou Uprising was a failure.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Under pressure from the Qing government, the government of Hong Kong banned the two men from the territory for five years.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun went into exile; promoted revolution; and raised funds in Japan, the United States, Canada, and Britain.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1901, following the Huizhou Uprising, Yeung Ku-wan was assassinated by Qing agents in Hong Kong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After his death, his family protected his identity by not putting his name on his tomb, just the number "6348".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In 1900, after the Boxer Rebellion started, Tang Caichang (唐才常) and Tan Sitong of the previous Foot Emancipation Society organized the Independence Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Independence Army Uprising (自立軍起義) was planned to occur on 23 August 1900.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Their goal was to overthrow Empress Dowager Cixi to establish a constitutional monarchy under the Guangxu Emperor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Their plot was discovered by the governors-general of Hunan and Hubei.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] About twenty conspirators were arrested and executed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 8 October 1900, Sun ordered the launch of the Huizhou uprising (惠州起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionary army was led by Zheng Shiliang and initially included 20,000 men, who fought for half a month.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] However, after Japanese Prime Minister Hirobumi Ito prohibited Sun Yat-sen from carrying out revolutionary activities in Taiwan, Zheng Shiliang had no choice but to order the army to disperse.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A very short uprising occurred from 25 to 28 January 1903 in an attempt to establish a "Great Ming Heavenly Kingdom" (大明順天國).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It involved Tse Tsan-tai, Li Jitang (李紀堂), Liang Muguang (梁慕光), and Hong Quanfu (洪全福), who had taken part in the Jintian uprising during the Taiping Heavenly Kingdom era.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Ma Fuyi (馬福益) and Huaxinghui was involved in an uprising in the areas of Pingxiang, Liuyang, and Liling (萍瀏醴起義) in 1905.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Ping-liu-li Uprising had recruited miners as early as 1903 to rise against the Qing ruling class.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the uprising failed, Ma Fuyi was executed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Wu Yue (吳樾) of the Guangfuhui carried out an assassination attempt at the Beijing Zhengyangmen East Railway station (正陽門車站) in an attack on five Qing officials on 24 September 1905.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Huanggang uprising (黃岡起義) was launched on 22 May 1907, in Chaozhou.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionary party, along with Xu Xueqiu (許雪秋), Chen Yongpo (陳湧波), and Yu Tongshi (余通實), launched the uprising and captured the city of Huanggang.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the uprising began, the Qing government quickly and forcefully suppressed it.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In the same year, Sun sent more revolutionaries to Huizhou to launch the "Huizhou Qinühu uprising" (惠州七女湖起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 2 June, Deng Zhiyu (鄧子瑜) and Chen Chuan (陳純) gathered some followers, and together they seized Qing arms in the lake, 20 km (12 mi) from Huizhou.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They killed several Qing soldiers and attacked Taiwei (泰尾) on 5 June.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing army fled in disorder, and the revolutionaries exploited the opportunity, captured several towns, and defeated the Qing army once again in Bazhiyie.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many organizations voiced their support after the uprising, and the revolutionary forces were 200 men at its height.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The uprising, however, ultimately failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 6 July 1907, Xu Xilin of Guangfuhui led an uprising in Anqing, Anhui, which became known as the Anqing Uprising (安慶起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Xu, the police commissioner and the supervisor of the police academy, led an uprising that aimed to assassinate the provincial governor of Anhui, En Ming (恩銘).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They were defeated after four hours of fighting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Xu was captured, and En Ming's bodyguards cut out his heart and liver and ate them.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] His cousin Qiu Jin was executed a few days later.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] From August to September 1907, the Qinzhou uprising occurred (欽州防城起義) against heavy taxation by the government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun sent Wang Heshun (王和順) there to assist the revolutionary army and captured the county in September.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They attempted to besiege and capture Qinzhou but eventually had retreat to the area of Shiwandashan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 1 December 1907, the Zhennanguan uprising (鎮南關起事) took place at Zhennanguan along the Chinese-Vietnamese border.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun Yat-sen sent Huang Mintang (黃明堂) to monitor the pass, which was guarded by a fort.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] With the assistance of supporters among the fort's defenders, the revolutionaries captured the cannon tower in Zhennanguan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun, Huang Xing. and Hu Hanmin personally went to the tower to command the battle.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing government sent troops led by Long Jiguang and Lu Rongting to counterattack, and the revolutionaries were forced to retreat into the mountainous areas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the uprising's failure, Sun was forced to move to Singapore due to anti-Sun sentiments within the revolutionary groups.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] He returned to the mainland only after the Wuchang Uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 27 March 1908, Huang Xing launched a raid, later known as the Qin-Lian uprising (欽廉上思起義), from a base in Vietnam and attacked the cities of Qinzhou and Lianzhou, in Guangdong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The rebels continued for fourteen days but were forced to end after the revolutionaries ran out of supplies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In April 1908, another uprising was launched in Yunnan, Hekou, called the Hekou uprising (雲南河口起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Huang Mingtang (黃明堂) led two hundred men from Vietnam and attacked Hekou on 30 April.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Other participating revolutionaries included Wang Heshun (王和順) and Guan Renfu (關仁甫).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They were outnumbered and defeated by government troops, however, and the uprising failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 19 November 1908, the Mapaoying Uprising (馬炮營起義) was launched by the revolutionary group Yuewanghui (岳王會), led by Xiong Chenggei (熊成基) in Anhui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In February 1910, the Gengxu New Army Uprising (庚戌新軍起義), also known as the Guangzhou New Army Uprising (廣州新軍起義), took place.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] That involved a conflict between the citizens and local police against the New Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the revolutionary leader Ni Yingdian was killed by Qing forces, the remaining revolutionaries were quickly defeated, and the uprising failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 27 April 1911, an uprising occurred in Guangzhou, known as the Second Guangzhou Uprising (辛亥廣州起義) or Yellow Flower Mound Revolt (黃花岡之役).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It ended in disaster, as 86 bodies were found (only 72 could be identified).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The 72 revolutionaries were remembered as martyrs.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionary Lin Juemin was one of the 72.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On the eve of battle, he wrote "A Letter to My Wife" (與妻訣別書), which later became considered a masterpiece in Chinese literature.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Literary Society (文學社) and the Progressive Association (共進會) were revolutionary organizations that involved in the uprising that began mainly by a Railway Protection Movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In the late summer, some Hubei New Army units were ordered to neighboring Sichuan to quell the Railway Protection Movement, a mass protest against the Qing government's seizure and handover of local railway development ventures to foreign powers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Banner officers like Duanfang, the railway superintendent, and Zhao Erfeng led the New Army against the Railway Protection Movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The New Army units of Hubei had originally been the Hubei Army, which had been trained by Qing official Zhang Zhidong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 24 September, the Literary Society and Progressive Association convened a conference in Wuchang, along with sixty representatives from local New Army units.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] During the conference, they established a headquarters for the uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The leaders of the two organizations, Jiang Yiwu (蔣翊武) and Sun Wu (孫武), were elected as commander and chief of staff.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Initially, the date of the uprising was to be 6 October 1911.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It was postponed because of insufficient preparations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Revolutionaries intent on overthrowing the Qing dynasty had built bombs, and on 9 October, one of them accidentally exploded.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sun had no direct part in the uprising and was traveling in the United States to recruit more support from overseas Chinese.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing Viceroy of Huguang, Rui Cheng (瑞澂), tried to track down and arrest the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The squad leader Xiong Bingkun (熊秉坤) and others decided not to delay the uprising any longer and launched the revolt on 10 October 1911, at 7:00 p.m.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolt was a success; the entire city of Wuchang had been captured by the revolutionaries on the morning of 11 October.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] That evening, they established a tactical headquarters and announced the establishment of the "Military Government of Hubei of Republic of China".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The conference chose Li Yuanhong as the governor of the temporary government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Qing officers like the bannermen Duanfang and Zhao Erfeng were killed by the revolutionary forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Revolutionaries killed a German arms dealer in Hankou as he was delivering arms to the Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Revolutionaries killed 2 Germans and wounded 2 other Germans at the battle of Hanyang, including a former colonel.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the success of the Wuchang Uprising, many other protests occurred throughout the country for various reasons.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some uprisings declared restoration (光復) of Han Chinese rule.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Other uprisings were a step toward independence, and some were protests or rebellions against the local authorities.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Regardless of the reason for the uprising, the outcome was that all of the provinces renounced the Qing dynasty and joined the republicans.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 22 October 1911, the Hunan Tongmenghui were led by Jiao Dafeng (焦達嶧) and Chen Zuoxin (陳作新).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They headed an armed group, consisting partly of revolutionaries from Hongjiang and defecting New Army units, in a campaign to extend the uprising into Changsha.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They captured the city and killed the local Imperial general.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They announced the establishment of the Hunan Military Government of the Republic of China and announced their opposition to the Qing Empire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On the same day, the Shaanxi Tongmenghui, led by Jing Dingcheng (景定成), Qian Ding (錢鼎), and Jing Wumu (井勿幕), and others including the Gelaohui, launched an uprising and captured Xi'an after two days of fighting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Hui Muslim community was divided in its support for the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Hui Muslims of Shaanxi supported the revolutionaries, and the Hui Muslims of Gansu supported the Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The native Hui of Xi'an joined the Han Chinese revolutionaries in slaughtering the Manchus.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The native Hui Muslims of Gansu province led by general Ma Anliang led more than twenty battalions of Hui troops to defend the Qing imperials and attacked Shaanxi, held by revolutionary Zhang Fenghui (張鳳翽).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The attack was successful, and after news arrived that Puyi was about to abdicate, Ma agreed to join the new Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries established the "Qinlong Fuhan Military Government" and elected Zhang Fenghui, a member of the Yuanrizhi Society (原日知會), as new governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After the Xi'an Manchu quarter fell on 24 October, Xinhai forces killed all the Manchus in the city, about 20,000.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many of its Manchu defenders committed suicide, including Qing General Wenrui (文瑞), who threw himself down a well.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Only some wealthy Manchus who were ransomed and Manchu females survived.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Wealthy Han Chinese seized Manchu girls to become their slaves, and poor Han Chinese troops seized young Manchu women to be their wives.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Young Manchu girls were also seized by Hui Muslims of Xi'an during the massacre and brought up as Muslims.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Hui General Ma Anliang abandoned the Qing cause upon the Qing abdication in the Xinhai Revolution, and the Manchu governor general Shengyun was enraged at the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Pro-revolution Hui Muslims like Shaanxi Governor Ma Yugui and Beijing Imam Wang Kuan persuaded Qing Hui General Ma Anliang to stop fighting by telling him that Muslims should not kill one another for the sake of the Qing monarchists but side with the republican revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Ma Anliang then agreed to abandon the Qing under the combination of Yuan Shikai's actions and those messages from other Hui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A year before the massacre of Manchus in October 1911, an oath against them had been sworn at the Great Goose Pagoda in Xi'an by the Gelaohui in 1911.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The southern part of Xi'an was entirely Han.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Xi'an had the biggest Manchu banner garrison quarter by area before its destruction.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 22 October 1911, the revolutionaries were led by students of the military academy who overcame the guards at the gates of Xi'an and shut them.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They secured the arsenal, slaughtered all Manchus at their temple, and then stormed and slaughtered the Manchus in the Manchu banner quarter of the city.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Manchu quarter was set on fire, burning many Manchus alive.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many Manchus had stored gunpowder in their houses, which exploded from the fire and caused even more deaths.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] For three days, Manchu men, women and children alike were slaughtered.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Only after that were Manchu women and girls spared, while Manchu men and boys continued to be slaughtered.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Many Manchus committed suicide by overdosing on opium and throwing themselves into wells.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It was estimated that between 10,000 and 20,000 Manchus were slaughtered.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Ma Anliang was ordered to attack the revolutionaries in Shaanxi by the baoyi bondservant Chang Geng and Manchu Shengyun.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Eastern soldiers of the new republic were mobilized by Yuan Shikai when the attack against Shaanxi began by Ma Anliang, but news of the abdication of the Qing Emperor reached Ma Anliang before he attacked Xi'an.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] That made Ma end all military operations and change his allegiance to the Republic of China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] All pro-Qing military activity in the northwest was then put to an end.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Yuan Shikai managed to induce Ma not to attack Shaanxi after the Gelaohui took over the province and to accept the Republic of China under his presidency in 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] During the National Protection War in 1916 between republicans and Yuan's monarchy, Ma readied his soldiers and informed the republicans that he and the Muslims would stick to Yuan until the end.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Yuan Shikai ordered Ma Anliang to block Bai Lang (White Wolf) from going into Sichuan and Gansu by blocking Hanzhong and Fengxiangfu.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Protestant Shensi mission operated a hospital in Xian.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some American missionaries were reported killed in Xi'an.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A report claimed Manchus massacred missionaries in the suburbs of Xi'an.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Missionaries were reported killed in Xi'an and Taiyuan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Shaanxi joined the revolution on October 24.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Sheng Yun was governor of Shaanxi in 1905.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some Gansu Hui, led by Ma Fuxiang, joined the republicans.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 23 October, Lin Sen, Jiang Qun (蔣群), Cai Hui (蔡蕙), and other members of the Tongmenghui in the province of Jiangxi plotted a revolt of New Army units.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] A Qing naval fleet also revolted against the state, which solidified victory in the Wuchang Uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] After they achieved victory, they announced their independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Jiujiang Military Government was then established.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 29 October, Yan Xishan of the New Army led an uprising in Taiyuan, the capital city of the province of Shanxi.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The rebels in Taiyuan bombarded the streets where Banner people resided and killed all the Manchu.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They managed to kill the Qing Governor of Shanxi, Lu Zhongqi (陸鍾琦).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They then announced the establishment of Shanxi Military Government with Yan Xishan as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 30 October, Li Genyuan (李根源) of the Tongmenghui in Yunnan joined with Cai E, Luo Peijin (羅佩金), Tang Jiyao, and other officers of the New Army to launch the Double Ninth Uprising (重九起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They captured Kunming the next day, established the Yunnan Military Government, and chose Cai E as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 31 October, the Nanchang branch of the Tongmenghui-led New Army units in a successful uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They established the Jiangxi Military Government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Li Liejun was elected as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Li declared Jiangxi as independent and launched an expedition against Qing official Yuan Shikai.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 3 November, the Shanghai Tongmenghui and Guangfuhui and merchants led by Chen Qimei, Li Pingsu (李平書), Zhang Chengyou (張承槱), Li Yingshi (李英石), Li Xiehe (李燮和), and Song Jiaoren organized an armed rebellion in Shanghai.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They received support from local police officers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The rebels captured the Jiangnan Workshop on the 4th and captured Shanghai soon afterward.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 8 November, they established the Shanghai Military Government and elected Chen Qimei as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] He would eventually become one of the founders of the four big families of the Republic of China, along with some of the most well-known families of the era.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 4 November, Zhang Bailin (張百麟) of the revolutionary party in Guizhou led an uprising, along with New Army units and students from the military academy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They immediately captured Guiyang, established the Great Han Guizhou Military Government, and chose Yang Jincheng (楊藎誠) and Zhao Dequan (趙德全) as respectively the chief and vice governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Also on 4 November, revolutionaries in Zhejiang urged the New Army units in Hangzhou to launch an uprising.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Zhu Rui (朱瑞), Wu Siyu (吳思豫), Lu Gongwang (吕公望) and others of the New Army captured the military supplies workshop.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Other units, led by Chiang Kai-shek and Yin Zhirei (尹銳志), captured most of the government offices.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Eventually, Hangzhou was under the control of the revolutionaries, and the constitutionalist Tang Shouqian (湯壽潛) was chosen as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 5 November, the Jiangsu constitutionalists and gentry urged Qing Governor Cheng Dequan (程德全) to declare independence and established the Jiangsu Revolutionary Military Government with Cheng himself as the governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Unlike some other cities, anti-Manchu violence began after the restoration on 7 November in Zhenjiang.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Qing General Zaimu (載穆) agreed to surrender, but because of a misunderstanding, the revolutionaries were unaware that their safety was guaranteed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Manchu quarters were ransacked, and an unknown number of Manchus were killed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Zaimu, feeling betrayed, committed suicide.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] This is regarded as the Zhenjiang Uprising (鎮江起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Members of the Anhui Tongmenghui also launched an uprising on that day and laid siege to the provincial capital.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The constitutionalists persuaded Zhu Jiabao, the Qing governor of Anhui, to declare independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 7 November, the Guangxi political department decided to secede from the Qing government and declared Guangxi's independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Qing Governor Shen Bingkun (沈秉堃) was allowed to remain, but Lu Rongting soon became the new governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Lu Rongting would later rise to prominence during the Warlord Era, and his bandits controlled Guangxi for more than a decade.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Under leadership of Huang Shaohong, the Muslim law student Bai Chongxi was enlisted into a Dare to Die unit to fight as a revolutionary.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In November, members of Fujian's branch of the Tongmenghui, along with Sun Daoren (孫道仁) of the New Army, launched an uprising against the Qing army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing viceroy, Song Shou (松壽), committed suicide.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 11 November, the entire Fujian province declared independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Fujian Military Government was established, and Sun Daoren was chosen as the military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Near the end of October, Chen Jiongming, Deng Keng (鄧鏗), Peng Reihai (彭瑞海), and other members of Guangdong's Tongmenghui organized local militias to launch the uprising in Huazhou, Nanhai, Sunde and Sanshui in Guangdong Province.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 8 November, after being persuaded by Hu Hanmin, General Li Zhun (李準) and Long Jiguang (龍濟光) of the Guangdong Navy agreed to support the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing viceroy of Liangguang, Zhang Mingqi (張鳴岐), was forced to discuss with local representatives a proposal for Guangdong's independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They decided to declare it the next day.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 9 November, Guangdong declared its independence and established a military government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They elected Hu Hanmin and Chen Jiongming as Chief and Vice-Governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Qiu Fengjia is known to have helped make the declaration of independence more peaceful.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] It was unknown at the time if representatives from the European colonies of Hong Kong and Macau would be ceded to the new government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On November 12, 1911, members of the Tongmenghui in Yantai, Shandong, including Luan Zhongyao (欒鍾堯) and Gong Xide (宮錫德)—collectively known as the "Eighteen Heroes"—launched an uprising and seized the Yantai Coastal Defense Battalion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Upon learning of the revolt, the Yantai Circuit Intendant Xu Shiguang fled with his family to seek protection at the residence of the British official, head of the Donghai Customs (東海關稅務司).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On November 13, the "Eighteen Heroes" sent a telegram to the Shanghai Military Governor Chen Qimei, declaring Yantai's independence and announcing the establishment of the Shandong Military Government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The following day, it was renamed the Shandong–Yantai Military and Political Sub-Administration, and Wang Chuanjiong, captain of the Qing Navy warship Wufeng, was elected commander-in-chief of the Yantai Military and Political Sub-Administration.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On November 13, under the persuasion of the Shandong revolutionary Ding Weifen (丁惟汾) and coercion from some officers, including acting commander Jia Binqing of the Fifth New Army Division, the Governor of Shandong Sun Baoqi agreed to declare Shandong's independence and was elected military governor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On November 24, however, Sun Baoqi again rescinded the declaration of independence under pressure from the Fifth New Army Division.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Yuan Shikai ordered Zhang Guangjian to be promoted from sub-prefectural magistrate to provincial administration commissioner, and Wu Bingxiang to be promoted from reserve assistant magistrate to commissioner of police affairs.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] They launched a crackdown on revolutionaries, ordering police to erase all street posters bearing the slogan "Over four thousand years since the Yellow Emperor" and replace them with notices bearing the reign year of Xuantong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Fourteen revolutionaries, including Liu Pulin and Du Jin, were arrested.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Lan Shengjiu was beaten to death on the spot with rifle butts, and property from both shops was looted.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] This incident is historically known as the Yichun Studio Massacre.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 17 November, the Ningxia Tongmenghui launched the Ningxia uprising (寧夏會黨起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries sent Yu Youren to Zhangjiachuan to meet the Dungan Sufi master Ma Yuanzhang to persuade him not to support the Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] However, Ma did not want to endanger his relationship with the Qings.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] He sent the eastern Gansu Muslim militia under the command of one of his sons to help Ma Qi fight the Ningxia Gelaohui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Ma Anliang, Changgeng, and Shengyun failed to capture Shaanxi from the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In Ningxia, Qing forces were attacked by both Hui Muslim Gelaohui and Han Gelaohui members, and Hui General Ma Qi and Ma Yuanzhang were in the Qing forces fighting against them, Hoverver, Ma Yuanzhang defected to the republicans after Ma Anliang had given up on the Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] However, the Ningxia Revolutionary Military Government was established on 23 November.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some revolutionaries involved included Huang Yue (黃鉞) and Xiang Shen (向燊), who gathered New Army forces at Qinzhou (秦州).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 21 November, Guang'an organized the Great Han Shu Northern Military Government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 22 November, Chengdu and Sichuan declared independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] By the 27th, the Great Han Sichuan Military Government had been established, headed by revolutionary Pu Dianzun (蒲殿俊).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The Qing official Duanfang would also be killed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 8 November, supported by the Tongmenghui, Xu Shaozhen (徐紹楨) of the New Army announced an uprising in Molin Pass (秣陵關), 30 km (19 mi) away from Nanjing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Xu Shaozhen, Chen Qimei and other generals decided to form a united army under Xu to strike Nanjing together.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 11 November, the united army headquarters was established in Zhenjiang.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Between 24 November and 1 December, under the command of Xu Shaozhen, the united army captured Wulongshan (烏龍山), Mufushan (幕府山)), Yuhuatai (雨花臺)), Tianbao (天保城)) among other Qing army strongholds.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 2 December, Nanjing was captured by the revolutionaries after the Battle of Nanjing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 3 December, revolutionary Su Liangbi led troops in a massacre of a large number of Manchus.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Shortly afterward, he was arrested, and his troops were disbanded.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] In Xinjiang on 28 December, Liu Xianzun (劉先俊) and revolutionaries started the Dihua Uprising (迪化起義).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] This was led by more than 100 members of Gelaohui.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 7 January 1912, the Yili Uprising (伊犁起義) with Feng Temin began.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Qing governor Yuan Dahua (袁大化) fled and submitted his resignation to Yang Zengxin because he could not handle fighting the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] On 8 January, a new Yili government was established for the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Some Chinese historians now believe that contributed to the Qing dynasty's fall because it prevented the Qing's plan to flee to the west.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries would be defeated at Jinghe in January and February; Eventually, the abdication to come would make Yuan Shikai recognize Yang Zengxin's rule and appoint him Governor of Xinjiang, and the province join the republicans.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] Eleven more former Qing officials would be assassinated in Zhenxi, Karashahr, Aksu, Kucha, Luntai, and Kashgar in April and May 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries printed new multilingual media.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Qing sent Zhao Erfeng to Tibet to fight the 1905 Tibetan Rebellion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] By 1908, Zhao was appointed imperial resident in Lhasa.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Zhao was beheaded in December 1911 by pro-Republican forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The bulk of the area historically known as Kham was now claimed to be the Xikang Administrative District, created by the republican revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] By the end of 1912, the last Qing troops had been forced out of Tibet through India.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Thubten Gyatso, the 13th Dalai Lama, returned to Tibet in January 1913 from Sikkim, where he had been residing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] That has many read the reply as a formal declaration of independence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Chinese side ignored the response, and Tibet was free of interference from China until 1951.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] At the end of 1911, Outer Mongolia took action with an armed revolt against Qing authorities but was unsuccessful.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The independence movement that took place was not limited to Outer Mongolia but was a pan-Mongolian phenomenon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 29 December 1911, Bogd Khan became the ruler of the Bogd Khanate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Inner Mongolia became a contested terrain between the Bogd Khanate and China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] In general, Russia supported the independence of Outer Mongolia (including Tannu Uriankhai) during the 1911 Revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Tibet and Outer Mongolia then recognized each other in a treaty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] In 1919, the Republic of China regained Outer Mongolia but lost it again in 1921.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] China, a member of the United Nations, has officially recognized the independence of Outer Mongolia since 1949.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Taiwan opened a cultural representative office and economy as part of its recognition of Mongolia in 2002.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 1 November 1911, the Qing government appointed Yuan Shikai as Prime Minister of the imperial cabinet, replacing Prince Qing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 3 November, after a proposition by Cen Chunxuan from the Constitutional Monarchy Movement, the Qing court passed the Nineteen Articles, which turned the Qing from an absolute monarchy to a constitutional monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 9 November, Huang Xing even cabled Yuan Shikai and invited him to join the Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The changes were too late, and the Emperor was about to be forced to abdicate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 28 November 1911, Wuchang and Hanyang had fallen back to the Qing army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] For their safety, the revolutionaries convened their first conference at the British Concession in Hankou on 30 November.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] By 2 December, the revolutionary forces were able to capture Nanking in the uprising; and the revolutionaries decided to make it the site of the new provisional government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] At the time, Beijing was still the Qing capital.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 18 December, the North–South Conference was held in Shanghai to discuss issues in the north and the south.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The reluctance of foreign financiers to give financial support to the Qing government or the revolutionaries contributed to both sides agreeing to start negotiations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Yuan Shikai selected Tang Shaoyi as his representative.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Tang left Beijing for Wuhan to negotiate with the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] With the intervention of six foreign powers (the United Kingdom, the United States, Germany, Russia, Japan, and France), Tang Shaoyi and Wu Tingfang began to negotiate a settlement at the British concession.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The foreign businessman Edward Selby Little (李德立) acted as the negotiator and facilitated the peace agreement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] They agreed that Yuan Shikai would force the Qing emperor to abdicate in exchange for the southern provinces' support of him as President of the Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] After considering the possibility that the new republic might be defeated in a civil war or by foreign invasion, Sun agreed to Yuan's proposal to unify China under Yuan Shikai's Beijing government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Further decisions were made to let the Emperor rule over his small court in the New Summer Palace.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] He would be treated as a ruler of a separate country and have expenses of several million taels in silver.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 29 December 1911, Sun Yat-sen was elected as the first provisional president, and 1 January 1912 was set as the first day of the First Year of the Republic of China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 3 January, the representatives recommended Li Yuanhong as the Provisional Vice-president.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] During and after the 1911 Revolution, many groups that participated wanted their own pennant as the national flag.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] During the Wuchang Uprising, the military units of Wuchang wanted the nine-star flag with a taijitu.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Others in competition included Lu Haodong's Blue Sky with a White Sun flag.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Huang Xing preferred a flag bearing the mythical "well-field" system of village agriculture.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] In the end, the assembly compromised: the national flag would be the banner of Five Races Under One Union.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Five Races Under One Union flag with horizontal stripes represented the five major nationalities of the republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The red represented Han, the yellow represented Manchus, the blue for Mongols, the white for Muslims, and the black for Tibetans.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Although the general targets of the uprisings were the Manchus, Sun Yat-sen, Song Jiaoren and Huang Xing advocated racial integration to be carried out from the mainland to the frontiers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 16 January, while returning to his residence, Yuan was ambushed in a bomb attack that was organized by the Tongmenghui in Donghuamen, Beijing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] About ten guards died, but Yuan himself was not seriously injured.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] He sent a message to the revolutionaries the next day that pledged his loyalty and asked them to organize no more assassination attempts against him.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Zhang Jian drafted an abdication proposal, which was approved by the Provisional Senate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 20 January, Wu Tingfang of the Nanking Provisional Government officially delivered the Imperial Edict of Abdication to Yuan Shikai for the abdication of Puyi.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 22 January, Sun Yat-sen announced that he would resign the presidency in favor of Yuan Shikai if the latter supported the Emperor's abdication.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 3 February, Longyu gave Yuan full permission to negotiate the abdication terms of the Qing emperor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Yuan then drew up his own version and forwarded it to the revolutionaries on 3 February.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] His version had three, instead of two, sections.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 12 February, after they were pressured by Yuan and other ministers, the six-year-old Puyi and Empress Dowager Longyu accepted Yuan's terms of abdication.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] As a condition for ceding leadership to Yuan, Sun insisted that the provisional government remain in Nanjing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 14 February, the Provisional Senate initially voted 20–5 for making Beijing the capital over Nanjing, with two votes going for Wuhan and one for Tianjin.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Senate majority wanted to secure the peace agreement by taking power in Beijing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Zhang Jian and others reasoned that having the capital in Beijing would prevent restoration of the Manchus and the secession of the Mongols.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] However, Sun and Huang Xing argued for Nanjing to balance against Yuan's power base in the north.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Li Yuanhong presented Wuhan as a compromise.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The next day, the Provisional Senate voted again, this time 19–6, for Nanjing, with two votes for Wuhan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Sun sent a delegation led by Cai Yuanpei and Wang Jingwei to persuade Yuan to move to Nanjing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Yuan welcomed the delegation and agreed to accompany the delegates back to the south.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Then on the evening of 29 February, riots and fires broke out all over the city.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] They were allegedly started by disobedient troops of Cao Kun, a officer loyal to Yuan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The disorder gave Yuan a pretext to stay in the north to guard against unrest.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 10 March, Yuan was inaugurated in Beijing as the Provisional President of the Republic of China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 5 April, the Provisional Senate in Nanjing voted to make Beijing the capital of the Republic and convened in Beijing at the end of the month.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] On 10 March 1912, Yuan Shikai was sworn as the second Provisional President of the Republic of China in Beijing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The first National Assembly election took place according to the Provisional Constitution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] While in Beijing, the Kuomintang was formed on 25 August 1912.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Nationalists held the majority of seats after the election.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] However, Song was assassinated in Shanghai on 20 March 1913 under a secret order by Yuan.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Some advocated that an ethnic Han be installed as Emperor of China, either a descendant of Confucius who held the noble title of the Duke of Yansheng or a descendant of the Ming imperial family who had the title of the Marquis of Extended Grace.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Duke of Yansheng was proposed as a candidate for emperorship by Liang Qichao.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The Han hereditary aristocratic nobility, like the Duke of Yansheng, was retained by the new Republic of China, and the title's holders continued to receive their pensions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] A plan backed by foreign bankers was reportedly in place to declare the Duke of Yansheng as Emperor of China if the revolutionaries' republican cause had failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] After the revolution, there was a huge outpouring of anti-Manchu sentiment through China, particularly in Beijing, where thousands died in anti-Manchu violence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Imperial restrictions on Han residency and behavior within the city crumbled with the Manchu's imperial power.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Anti-Manchu sentiment is recorded in books like *A Short History of Slaves* (奴才小史) and *The Biographies of Avaricious Officials and Corrupt Personnel* (貪官污吏傳) by Laoli (老吏).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] During the abdication of the last Emperor, Yuan Shikai and Sun Yat-sen tried to adopt the concept of "Manchu and Han as one family" (滿漢一家).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] People started exploring and debating with themselves on the root cause of their national weakness.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The new search of identity was the New Culture Movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Manchu culture and language, on the contrary, became virtually extinct by 2007.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Unlike revolutions in the West, the 1911 Revolution did not restructure society.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Most participants in the 1911 Revolution were military personnel, traditional bureaucrats, and local gentries and kept their regional power afterward.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] There were no major improvements in the standard of living.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The 1911 Revolution mainly got rid of feudalism (fengjian) from the late imperial period.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The usual view of historians has two restorations of feudal power after the revolution: Yuan Shikai, followed by Zhang Xun.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The effects of anti-Manchu sentiment after the revolution caused the Manchus of the Metropolitan Banners to be driven into deep poverty.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Manchu men were too impoverished to marry, Han men married Manchu women, and the Manchus stopped dressing in Manchu clothing and practicing Manchu traditions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The 1911 Revolution overthrew the Qing government and four thousand years of monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Throughout Chinese history, old dynasties had always been replaced by new dynasties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The 1911 Revolution, however, was the first to overthrow a monarchy completely and attempt to establish a republic to spread democratic ideas throughout China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] In 1911 at the provisional government proclamation ceremony, Sun Yat-sen said, "The revolution is not yet successful, the comrades still need to strive for the future." (革命尚未成功，同志仍需努力).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Since the 1950s, both Chinas have seen the 1911 Revolution quite differently.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Both recognize Sun Yat-sen as the Father of the Nation, but in Taiwan, "Father of the Republic of China" is meant.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] In Mainland China, Sun Yat-sen was seen as the man who helped bring down the Qing, a precondition for the communist state that was founded in 1949.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] It views Sun's work as the first step toward the real revolution in 1949, when the communists set up a truly-independent state, which expelled foreigners and built a military and industrial power.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The father of Communist China is seen as Mao Zedong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] A change in the belief that the revolution had been a generally positive began in the late 1980s and 1990s, but Zhang Shizhao was quoted as arguing, "When talking about the 1911 Revolution, the theorist these days tends to overemphasize.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] The degree of success of democracy gained by the revolution can vary depending on one's view.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Even after Sun Yat-sen died in 1925, the Nationalists controlled for sixty years all five branches of the government in Taiwan, and none was independent.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Yan Jiaqi, the founder of the Federation for a Democratic China, has said that Sun Yat-sen is to be credited as founding China's first republic in 1912, and the second republic is the people of Taiwan and the political parties, which now democratize the region.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Meanwhile, the ideals of democracy are far from realised in Mainland China.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] For example, the former Chinese Premier Wen Jiabao once said in a speech that without real democracy, there is no guarantee of economic and political rights, but he led a 2011 crackdown against the peaceful Chinese jasmine protests.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Others, such as Qin Yongmin of the Democracy Party of China, who was imprisoned for twelve years, do not praise the 1911 Revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Qin said that the revolution only replaced one dictator with another and that Mao is not an emperor but worse than the emperor.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] One of Japan's earliest film companies (M.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1911-revolution-p02] Pathe, owned by Sun supporter Shōkichi Umeya) documented the success of the revolution from the Wuchang uprising and to Sun's inauguration and produced three documentary films that covered the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:absolute-monarchy/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum regarding the prince's powers was held in Liechtenstein on 14 March 2003.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] The referendum had two questions: a "Princely Initiative" and a "Constitution Peace Initiative".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] The first question passed with 64.32% in favour and the second question was rejected by 83.44% of voters.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] The Princely Initiative asked voters whether to approve an extension of the power of the prince to dismiss the government, nominate judges and veto legislation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] The Constitution Peace Initiative asked voters whether to approve or disapprove of constitutional modifications, including modifications which would have restricted the prince's powers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] The BBC stated that the referendum in effect made Liechtenstein into an "absolute monarchy".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] In December 2002 the Venice commission of the Council of Europe published a comprehensive report analysing the amendments, opining that they were not compatible with the European standard of democracy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] Prince Hans-Adam II had threatened to leave the country and live in exile in Vienna, Austria if the voters had chosen to restrict his powers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2003-liechtenstein-constitutional-referendum] After the votes were counted, the prince told a local radio station: "It's an excellent result.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February 2022, during the Russo-Ukrainian war, Russia launched a full-scale invasion of Ukraine, starting the current phase of the war, the largest conflict in Europe since World War II.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By April 2022, the invasion's initial goal of a rapid Russian victory via decapitation had failed, with Ukraine pushing back the northern arm of the invasion and preventing the capture of Kyiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Following this, the war transitioned to more conventional fighting in the south and east of Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In a televised address, Russian president Vladimir Putin announced the invasion, calling it a "special military operation".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said that its purpose was to support the Russian-backed breakaway republics of Donetsk and Luhansk, whose paramilitary forces had been fighting Ukraine in the war in Donbas since 2014.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin espoused irredentist and imperialist views challenging Ukraine's legitimacy as a state, baselessly claimed that the Ukrainian government were neo-Nazis committing genocide against the Russian minority in the Donbas, and said that Russia's goal was to "demilitarise and denazify" Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In late 2021, Russia massed troops near Ukraine's borders and issued demands to the West including a ban on Ukraine ever joining the NATO military alliance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After repeatedly denying having plans to attack Ukraine, on 24 February 2022, Russian air strikes and a ground invasion were launched on a northern front from Belarus towards the capital Kyiv, a southern front from Crimea, and an eastern front from the Donbas and towards Kharkiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine enacted martial law, ordered a general mobilisation, and severed diplomatic relations with Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion was met with widespread international condemnation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The United Nations General Assembly passed a resolution condemning the invasion and demanding a full Russian withdrawal.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Court of Justice ordered Russia to halt military operations, and the Council of Europe expelled Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Many countries imposed sanctions on Russia and its ally Belarus and provided humanitarian and military aid to Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Baltic states and Poland declared Russia a terrorist state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests occurred around the world, with anti-war protesters in Russia being met by mass arrests and greater media censorship.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into crimes against humanity, war crimes, abduction of Ukrainian children, and genocide against Ukrainians.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The ICC issued arrest warrants for Putin and other Russian officials.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In 2013, Ukraine's parliament overwhelmingly approved finalising an association agreement with the European Union (EU), which had been negotiated for several years.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia put pressure on Ukraine to reject the agreement and imposed economic sanctions on the country.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin adviser Sergei Glazyev warned in September 2013 that if Ukraine signed the EU agreement, Russia would no longer acknowledge Ukraine's borders.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In November, Ukrainian president Viktor Yanukovych suddenly withdrew from signing the agreement, choosing closer ties to the Russian-led Eurasian Economic Union instead.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This coerced withdrawal triggered a wave of protests known as Euromaidan, culminating in the Revolution of Dignity in February 2014.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Despite signing an agreement, Yanukovych fled.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Parliament voted to remove him and he ended up in Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian soldiers with no insignia occupied the Ukrainian territory of Crimea, and seized the Crimean Parliament.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia annexed Crimea in March 2014, after a widely disputed referendum held under occupation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Pro-Russian protests immediately followed in the Ukrainian cities of Donetsk and Luhansk.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war in Donbas began in April 2014 when armed Russian mercenaries led by Igor 'Strelkov' Girkin seized Sloviansk and nearby towns.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops were covertly involved in the fighting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Minsk agreements, signed in September 2014 and February 2015, aimed to resolve the conflict, but ceasefires and further negotiations repeatedly failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] There was a large Russian military build-up near Ukraine's borders in March and April 2021, and again in both Russia and Belarus from October 2021 onward.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Members of the Russian government, including Putin, denied having plans to attack or invade Ukraine up until the day before the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] While Russian troops massed on Ukraine's borders, Russia's proxy forces launched thousands of attacks on Ukrainian forces in the Donbas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Observers from the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE), which also includes Ukraine and Russia, reported more than 90,000 ceasefire violations throughout 2021; the vast majority in Russian-controlled territory.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In July 2021, Putin published an essay "On the Historical Unity of Russians and Ukrainians", in which he called Ukraine "historically Russian lands" and claimed there is "no historical basis" for the "idea of Ukrainian people as a nation separate from the Russians".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin was accused of promoting Russian imperialism, historical revisionism and disinformation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024, Michael McFaul and Robert Person described this essay as representing not only "cynical propaganda" but also Putin's "deeply held and internalized beliefs".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In December 2021, Russia issued an ultimatum to the West, which included demands that NATO end all activity in its Eastern European member states and ban Ukraine or any other former Soviet state from ever joining the alliance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia's government said NATO was a threat and warned of a military response if it followed an "aggressive line".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg replied that "Russia has no veto" on whether Ukraine joins, and "has no right to establish a sphere of influence to try to control their neighbours".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Several Western political analysts suggested Russia knew that its "unrealistic demands" would be rejected, which would give it a pretext to invade.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political scientists Michael McFaul and Robert Person said Russia's occupation of Crimea and the Donbas since 2014 had already blocked Ukraine's NATO membership, suggesting that Putin's real aim was to subjugate Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] NATO offered to negotiate some of Russia's demands and to improve military transparency, as long as Russia stopped its troop buildup.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The alliance rejected Russia's demand to keep Ukraine out of NATO forever, pointing out that Russia had signed agreements affirming the right of Ukraine and other countries to join alliances.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The US proposed that itself and Russia sign an agreement not to station missiles or troops in Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin replied that Russia's demands had been "ignored", and the Russian troop buildup continued.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Western leaders vowed that heavy sanctions would be imposed should Putin choose to invade rather than to negotiate.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] French president Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz met Putin in February 2022 to dissuade him from invading.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Scholz, Putin told him that Ukraine should not be an independent state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Scholz told Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy to declare Ukraine a neutral country and renounce its aspirations to join NATO.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said Putin had broken agreements and could not be trusted to respect Ukrainian neutrality.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine had been a neutral country in 2014 when Russia occupied Crimea and invaded the Donbas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 19 February, Zelenskyy made a speech at the Munich Security Conference, calling for Western powers to end their "appeasement" of Putin and give a timeframe for when Ukraine could join NATO.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political analysts Taras Kuzio and Vladimir Socor agree that "when Russia made its decision to invade Ukraine, that country was more remote than ever not only from NATO membership but from any track that might lead to membership".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting in Donbas escalated from 17 February 2022.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainians and the Russian separatists accused one another of firing into their respective territories.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 February, the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics ordered all civilians to leave their capitals, although observers noted that full evacuations would take months.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian media reported a sharp increase in artillery shelling by the Russian-led militants in Donbas as an attempt to provoke the Ukrainian army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Separatist leaders warned that Ukraine was about to launch an offensive, but they gave no evidence, and *The Guardian* noted it would be "exceedingly risky" for Ukraine to assault the Donbas while Russian troops were massed on its borders.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy said his military would not respond to the provocations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the days leading up to the invasion, the Russian government intensified its disinformation campaign.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine and Western leaders accused Russia of staging false flag attacks to give Russia a pretext for invading.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian state media aired fabricated videos that purported to show Ukrainian forces attacking Russians in Donbas; evidence showed that the claimed attacks, explosions, and evacuations were staged by Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 17 February, Russian proxy forces shelled a kindergarten and blamed it on Ukraine, although the kindetgarten was in Ukrainian-held territory.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, the head of the Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) said that Russian forces had killed five Ukrainian "saboteurs" that crossed into Russian territory, capturing one Ukrainian serviceman and destroying two armoured vehicles.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The claim was denied by Ukraine and drew warnings that Russia was seeking further justification to start an invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 21 February, Putin announced that the Russian government would recognise the Donetsk and Luhansk people's republics.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, Putin directed that Russian troops be deployed to the Donbas, in what he called a "peacekeeping mission".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the same speech, Putin questioned the validity of the Ukrainian nation, stating that "Modern Ukraine was entirely created by Russia", views which Michael McFaul and Robert Person, writing in 2024, described as "grotesque".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The 21 February intervention in Donbas was condemned by several members of the UN Security Council; none voiced support.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 22 February, video footage shot in the early morning showed Russian armed forces and tanks moving in the Donbas region.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Federation Council unanimously authorised the use of military force outside Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Zelenskyy ordered the conscription of army reservists.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The following day, Ukraine's parliament proclaimed a 30-day nationwide state of emergency and ordered the mobilisation of all reservists.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia began to evacuate its embassy in Kyiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The websites of the Ukrainian parliament and government, along with banking websites, were hit by DDoS attacks, widely attributed to Russian-backed hackers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the night of 23 February, Zelenskyy gave a speech in Russian in which he appealed to the citizens of Russia to prevent war.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He also refuted Russia's claims about the presence of neo-Nazis in the Ukrainian government and said that he had no intention of attacking the Donbas region.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said on 23 February that the separatist leaders in Donetsk and Luhansk had sent a letter to Putin stating that Ukrainian shelling had caused civilian deaths and appealing for Russian military support.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In response, Ukraine requested an urgent UN Security Council meeting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Half an hour into the emergency meeting, Putin announced the start of military operations in Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sergiy Kyslytsya, the Ukrainian representative, subsequently called on the Russian representative, Vasily Nebenzya, to "do everything possible to stop the war" or relinquish his position as president of the UN Security Council; Nebenzya refused.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The decision to invade was reportedly made by Putin and a small group of war hawks or *siloviki* in Putin's inner circle, including national security adviser Nikolai Patrushev and defence minister Sergei Shoigu.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the start of the invasion, Ukrainian and Western analysts assessed that Putin seemed to have believed that the Russian Armed Forces would be capable of seizing Kyiv within days.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This assessment led to the conclusion that "taking Kyiv in three days" had been the original goal of the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The narrative of the planned "three day" capture of Kyiv was reinforced by statements by Aleksandr Lukashenko and Margarita Simonyan, editor-in-chief of Russian state-controlled broadcaster RT.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, the Security Service of Ukraine (SBU) repeated the claim following its release of a video showing a captured Russian soldier claiming that his unit was sent into Ukraine with food supplies for only three days.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Documents found inside Russian tanks mention how the "special military operation" would conclude in ten days.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine also captured "flagship" tanks – as used in parades – along with military parade uniforms, suggesting that Russia expected to stage a victory parade in Kyiv after a swift conquest.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin himself asserted back in 2014 that Russian forces "could take Ukraine in two weeks".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three days after the invasion began, RIA Novosti, a Russian state news agency, mistakenly published an article called "Russia's Coming and the New World", which had been made in advance in anticipation of a Russian victory; it announced that "Ukraine had returned to Russia".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy also said that Russia had sent him an ultimatum to step down and be replaced with Viktor Medvedchuk.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time on 24 February, Putin, in another speech, announced a "special military operation", which effectively declared war on Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said the operation was to "protect the people" of the Russian-controlled breakaway republics.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] He said Russia sought the "demilitarisation and denazification" of Ukraine, and denied the legitimacy of the Ukrainian state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin said he had no plans to occupy Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began within minutes of Putin's speech.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In order to justify the invasion of Ukraine within the context of international norms, Putin cited the 1999 NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and 2003 US invasion of Iraq.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion comprised nearly 150,000 troops, organised in about 140 Battalion Tactical Groups.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The forces of the Russia-controlled LNR and DNR, and paramilitary forces engaged in the invasion, raised total Russian-controlled forces employed in the campaign to as many as 200,000.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These forces were organised into groups having tactical signs to distinguish them, and were to advance into Ukraine along at least ten different axes of advance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Rather than having a unified command-structure, these groups were organised under different Russian military-district command-posts named after the region of Russia in which their respective military-district was located.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Three groups, all having the tactical sign "Z" and commanded by the Western Military District under Alexander Zhuravlyov, were to advance into Ukraine respectively from Kursk, Belgorod and Voronezh.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Groups under the Southern Military District under Aleksandr Dvornikov were identified with a "Z in a square" tactical symbol, and, advancing from occupied Crimea, were tasked with surrounding Mariupol, capturing Zaporizhia, seizing Kherson, and crossing the Dnieper river to take Voznesensk.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian regular forces involved in the invasion were equipped with roughly 2,800 tanks ready for combat, with another 400 approximately in the hands of the Russian-controlled proxy forces of the LNR and DNR.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces at the outbreak of the war comprised roughly 20 combat-ready brigades, of which more than half were located in the east of the country, positioned along the line of contact in the "Joint Forces Operation" zone in Donbas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] An additional manoeuvre brigade and two brigades of artillery were located in the Kyiv region, with other forces also deployed in the area of Kharkiv, Dnipro, Sumy, and Odesa.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] No major combat units were located on the Gomel or Crimean axes.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian tank-forces had roughly 900 battle-ready tanks organised in some 30 battalions at the time of the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of these tank battalions were formed in the period 2014–2018, when roughly 500 tanks were delivered to the Ukrainian armed forces, mostly reconditioned older tanks rather than new-built tanks, particularly T-64B and T-64-BM tanks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The tank battalions were spread between Ukraine's two regular and four reserve armoured brigades, as well as tank units attached to brigades of mechanised, mountain, airborne and marine infantry.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In contrast to the direct-fire techniques practised in most armoured forces, Ukrainian forces had, based on their experience during the war in Donbas, developed a technique of using tanks in the indirect-fire role.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This meant Ukrainian tank forces acting essentially as mobile artillery that did not require the kind of screening that traditional artillery units require.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion began at dawn on 24 February.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Fighting began in Luhansk Oblast at 3:40 a.m.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kyiv time near Milove on the border with Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The main infantry and tank attacks were launched in four spearheads, creating a northern front launched towards Kyiv from Belarus, a southern front from Crimea, a southeastern front from Russian-controlled Donbas, and an eastern front from Russia towards Kharkiv and Sumy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian vehicles were subsequently marked with a white *Z* military symbol (a non-Cyrillic letter), believed to be a measure to prevent friendly fire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Immediately after the invasion began, Zelenskyy declared martial law in Ukraine in a first video speech.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The same evening, he ordered a general mobilisation of all Ukrainian males between 18 and 60 years old, prohibiting them from leaving the country.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wagner Group mercenaries and Kadyrovites contracted by the Kremlin reportedly made several attempts to assassinate Zelenskyy, including an operation involving several hundred mercenaries meant to infiltrate Kyiv with the aim of killing the Ukrainian president.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Ukrainian government said anti-war officials within Russia's FSB shared the plans with them.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Zelenskyy appeared defiant in video messages on 24 through 26 February, that he and his cabinet is still in Kyiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February NATO met and its countries pledged military aid for Ukraine and on 27 February Germany called the invasion a historic watershed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] That day in the evening Putin put Russia's nuclear deterrence into alert.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian invasion was unexpectedly met by fierce Ukrainian resistance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Kyiv, Russia failed to take the city and was repulsed in the battles of Irpin, Hostomel, and Bucha.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians tried to encircle the capital, but its defenders under Oleksandr Syrskyi held their ground, effectively using Western Javelin anti-tank missiles and Stinger anti-aircraft missiles to thin Russian supply lines and stall the offensive.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the southern front, Russian forces had captured the regional capital of Kherson by 2 March.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A column of Russian tanks and armoured vehicles was ambushed on 9 March outside of Brovary and sustained heavy losses that forced them to retreat.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian army adopted siege tactics on the western front around the key cities of Chernihiv, Sumy and Kharkiv, but failed to capture them due to stiff resistance and logistical setbacks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In Mykolaiv Oblast, Russian forces advanced as far as Voznesensk, but were repelled and pushed back south of Mykolaiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A second axis, deployed towards eastern Kyiv from Russia by the Central Military District (northeastern front), comprised the 41st Combined Arms Army and the 2nd Guards Combined Arms Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third axis was deployed towards Kharkiv by the Western Military District (eastern front), with the 1st Guards Tank Army and 20th Combined Arms Army.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 7 April, Russian troops deployed to the northern front by the Russian Eastern Military District pulled back from the Kyiv offensive, reportedly to resupply and redeploy to the Donbas region in an effort to reinforce the renewed invasion of southeastern Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The northeastern front, including the Central Military District, was similarly withdrawn for resupply and redeployment to southeastern Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian efforts to capture Kyiv included a probative spearhead on 24 February, from Belarus south along the west bank of the Dnipro River.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The apparent intent was to encircle the city from the west, supported by two separate axes of attack from Russia along the east bank of the Dnipro: the western at Chernihiv, and from the east at Sumy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] These were likely intended to encircle Kyiv from the northeast and east.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia tried to seize Kyiv quickly, with Spetsnaz infiltrating into the city supported by airborne operations and a rapid mechanised advance from the north, but failed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reporter Glenn Kessler said it came from "a single source, but on the surface it appears to be a good one".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advancing on Kyiv from Belarus gained control of the ghost town of Chernobyl.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian Airborne Forces attempted to seize two key airfields near Kyiv, launching an airborne assault on Antonov Airport, and a similar landing at Vasylkiv, near Vasylkiv Air Base, on 26 February.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By early March, further Russian advances along the west side of the Dnipro were limited, after suffering setbacks from Ukrainian defence.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As of 5 March, a large Russian convoy, reportedly 64 kilometres (40 mi) in length, had made little progress toward Kyiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The London-based think tank Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) assessed the Russian performance from the north and east as "stalled".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Advances along the Chernihiv axis had largely halted as a siege of the city began.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also continued advancing from the northwest of Kyiv, capturing Bucha, Hostomel, and Vorzel by 5 March, though Irpin remained contested as of 9 March.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 11 March, it was reported that the lengthy convoy had largely dispersed, taking up positions that offered tree cover.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 16 March, Ukrainian forces began a counter-offensive to repel Russian forces approaching Kyiv from several surrounding cities.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 20 March, the Russian military appeared to be waging a rapid invasion to achieve its apparent primary goal of the seizure of Kyiv, along with the occupation of Eastern Ukraine and the overthrow of the Ukrainian government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Unable to achieve a quick victory in Kyiv, Russian forces switched strategies and began using standoff weapons, indiscriminate bombing, and siege warfare.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Ukrainian counteroffensive in Kyiv resulted in several towns, including Makariv, being retaken to the east and west of Kyiv.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] As part of a general retreat of Russian forces north of Kyiv, as well as attacks on Russian formations by the Ukrainian military, Russian troops in the Bucha area retreated north by the end of March.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukrainian forces entered the city on 1 April.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine claimed to recapture the entire region around Kyiv, including Irpin, Bucha, and Hostomel, by 2 April, with evidence of war crimes being uncovered in Bucha.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces advanced into Chernihiv Oblast on 24 February, besieging its administrative capital within four days of fighting.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February Ukrainian forces lost control over Konotop.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces also attacked Okhtyrka, deploying thermobaric weapons.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 4 March, Frederick Kagan wrote that the Sumy axis was then "the most successful and dangerous Russian avenue of advance on Kyiv", and commented that the geography favoured mechanised advances as the terrain "is flat and sparsely populated, offering few good defensive positions".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Travelling along highways, Russian forces reached Brovary, an eastern suburb of Kyiv, on 4 March.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Pentagon confirmed on 6 April that the Russian army had left Chernihiv Oblast, but Sumy Oblast remained contested.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 7 April, the governor of Sumy Oblast said that Russian troops were gone, but had left behind rigged explosives and other hazards.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces took control of the North Crimean Canal, allowing Crimea to obtain water from the Dnieper, which had been cut off since 2014.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 26 February, the siege of Mariupol began as the attack moved east linking to separatist-held Donbas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] En route, Russian forces entered Berdiansk and captured it.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, Russian units from the DPR were fighting near Pavlopil as they moved on Mariupol.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By evening, the Russian Navy began an amphibious assault on the coast of the Sea of Azov 70 kilometres (43 mi) west of Mariupol.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A US defence official said that Russian forces were deploying thousands of marines from this beachhead.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russian 22nd Army Corps approached the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant on 26 February and besieged Enerhodar.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A fire began, but the Ukrainian military said that essential equipment was undamaged.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] A third Russian attack group from Crimea moved northwest and captured the bridge over the Dnieper.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian troops took Kherson; this was the first major city to fall to Russian forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian troops moved on Mykolaiv and attacked it two days later.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After renewed missile attacks on 14 March in Mariupol, the Ukrainian government said more than 2,500 had died.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 18 March, Mariupol was completely encircled and fighting reached the city centre, hampering efforts to evacuate civilians.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 20 March, an art school sheltering around 400 people, was destroyed by Russian bombs.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The Russians demanded surrender, and the Ukrainians refused.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Putin told Emmanuel Macron in a phone call on 29 March that the bombardment of Mariupol would only end when the Ukrainians surrendered.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 April, Russian troops refused safe passage into Mariupol to 50 buses sent by the United Nations to evacuate civilians, as peace talks continued in Istanbul.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 3 April, following the retreat of Russian forces from Kyiv, Russia expanded its attack on southern Ukraine further west, with bombardment and strikes against Odesa, Mykolaiv, and the Zaporizhzhia Nuclear Power Plant.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the east, Russian troops attempted to capture Kharkiv, less than 35 kilometres (22 mi) from the Russian border, and met strong Ukrainian resistance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 February, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces with OTR-21 Tochka missiles, which according to Ukrainian officials, destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and started a fire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 1 March, Denis Pushilin, head of the DPR, announced that DPR forces had almost completely surrounded the city of Volnovakha.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March, Russian forces were repelled from Sievierodonetsk during an attack against the city.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On the same day, Ukrainian forces initiated a counter-offensive on Horlivka, controlled by the DPR.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Izium was captured by Russian forces on 1 April after a monthlong battle.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 25 March, the Russian defence ministry said it would seek to occupy major cities in eastern Ukraine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 31 March, *PBS News* reported renewed shelling and missile attacks in Kharkiv, as bad or worse than before, as peace talks with Russia were to resume in Istanbul.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Amid the heightened Russian shelling of Kharkiv on 31 March, Russia reported a helicopter strike against an oil supply depot approximately 35 kilometres (22 mi) north of the border in Belgorod, and accused Ukraine of the attack.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Local governor Maksym Kozytskyy reported that at least 35 people had been killed in the attacks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 18 March, Russia expanded the attack to Lviv, with Ukrainian military officials saying initial information suggested that the missiles which hit Lviv were likely air-launched cruise missiles originating from warplanes flying over the Black Sea.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, Russian forces attacked the Chuhuiv air base, which housed Bayraktar TB2 drones.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The attack caused damage to fuel storage areas and infrastructure.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The next day, the Millerovo air base was attacked by Ukrainian military forces using OTR-21 Tochka missiles.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Ukrainian officials, this destroyed several Russian Air Force planes and set the airbase on fire.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In the Zhytomyr Airport attack on 27 February, it was reported that Russia used 9K720 Iskander missile systems, located in Belarus, to attack the civilian Zhytomyr Airport.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia lost at least ten aircraft on 5 March.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 6 March, the General Staff of the Armed Forces of Ukraine reported that 88 Russian aircraft had been destroyed since the war began.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, an anonymous senior US defence official told Reuters on 7 March that Russia still had the "vast majority" of its fighter jets and helicopters that had been amassed near Ukraine available to fly.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] After the first month of the invasion, Justin Bronk, a British military observer, counted the Russian aircraft losses at 15 fixed-wing aircraft and 35 helicopters, but noted that the true total was certainly higher.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 13 March, Russian forces conducted multiple cruise missile attacks on a military training facility in Yavoriv, Lviv Oblast, close to the Polish border.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Ukraine lies on the Black Sea, which only has access through the Turkish-held Bosphorus and Dardanelles straits.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 28 February, Turkey invoked the 1936 Montreux Convention and sealed off the straits to Russian warships not registered as having Black Sea home bases and not returning to their ports of origin.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] This prevented the passage of four Russian naval vessels through the Turkish Straits.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 February, the State Border Guard Service of Ukraine announced that an attack on Snake Island by Russian Navy ships had begun.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The cruiser *Moskva* and patrol boat *Vasily Bykov* bombarded the island with their deck guns.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] When the Russian warship identified itself and instructed the Ukrainian soldiers stationed on the island to surrender, their response was "Russian warship, go fuck yourself!" After the bombardment, a detachment of Russian soldiers landed and took control of Snake Island.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia stated on 26 February that US drones were supplying intelligence to the Ukrainian navy to help target Russian warships in the Black Sea, which the US denied.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] By 3 March, the Ukrainian frigate *Hetman Sahaidachny*, the flagship of the Ukrainian navy, was scuttled in Mykolaiv to prevent its capture by Russian forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 14 March, the Russian source RT reported that the Russian Armed Forces had captured about a dozen Ukrainian ships in Berdiansk, including the *Polnocny*-class landing ship *Yuri Olefirenko*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 24 March, Ukrainian officials said that a Russian landing ship docked in Berdiansk was destroyed by a Ukrainian rocket attack.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Military analysts have been highly critical of the Russian plan of invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Kofman also criticised the use of "thunder runs" similar to those used by US forces in the 2003 Iraq war, in an environment where resistance to such attempts to go around urban centres was likely to be far higher.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The November 2022 Royal United Services Institute (RUSI) report on the invasion also criticised the invasion plan as being based on "false assumptions", and spreading Russian forces too thinly across too many objectives, with insufficient contingency-planning for what to do if things went wrong.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Nevertheless, RUSI also stated that "If competently executed, these plans could have succeeded".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Writing in 2024 in the *Journal of Strategic Studies*, analysts from the Swiss Military Academy at ETH Zurich characterised the invasion plan as being "predicated on a rapid, decisive overthrow of the government in Kyiv, presuming minimal resistance".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] They also criticised what they saw as the excessively rigid, Soviet-style command structure and operational planning of Russian forces during the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian air forces during the campaign were described by military analyst Sean M.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser, writing in 2023 in the *Small Wars & Insurgencies* journal, as having "bungled air operations from the outset of the war".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Wiswesser described the Russian air forces as having "settled largely for a 'tie'" during the period of the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The force-structure of Russian forces during the invasion has also been criticised, particularly the use of battalion tactical groups (BTGs), which proved brittle once Ukrainian resistance was met.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Whilst praising Ukraine's resistance to the invasion, analysts have also identified deficiencies in the deployment of Ukrainian forces before the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] At the tactical level, however, RUSI assessed Ukrainian forces as comprising "units which had been psychologically and practically preparing for this fight for eight years".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Alexander Hill described Ukrainian forces as having undergone a transformation since the fighting of 2014, and having become "a stubborn opponent that was typically difficult [for Russian troops] to dislodge".
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russian forces did not deploy an overall commander for the invasion of Ukraine, with command divided between the military district commanders, each of whom was assigned to their own axis of attack.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] According to Mason Clark of the Institute for the Study of War, this resulted in commanders competing for central resources and each effectively fighting their own war.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Subsequent to the failure of this strategy, according to Clark, Putin appointed Aleksandr Dvornikov as an overall commander in Ukraine on 8 April 2022, however Dvornikov retained his post as commander of the Southern Military District.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Disatisfied with Dvornikov's performance, according to Clark, Putin then dismissed Dvornikov as overall commander in June 2022 but allowed him to remain in overall command for several weeks, before Gennady Zhidko was reportedly appointed to that role.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] However, according to Clark, both Zhidko and Dvornikov were effectively "first among equals" among the Russian Military District Commanders rather than true theatre commanders, and it was not until October 2022 that a dedicated theatre commander - Sergey Surovikin - was appointed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia abandoned the attempt to take Kyiv in early April, but a lasting state of war between Russia and Ukraine remained, with Russia capturing Mariupol by 20 May 2022, and maintaining an occupation of large portions of four Ukrainian oblasts—Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk, and Zaporizhzhia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In August, Ukrainian forces began liberating territories in the north-east and south.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 30 September 2022, Russia declared the annexation of the four partially-occupied oblasts, which was internationally condemned.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most of Luhansk Oblast and part of Donetsk Oblast had been controlled by pro-Russian separatists since 2014, while the Kherson and Zaporizhzhia oblasts were invaded by Russia in 2022.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The boundaries of the areas to be annexed and their borders were not defined; Russian officials stated that they would be defined later.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] None of the oblasts were fully under Russian control at the time of the declaration, nor since.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] If limited to the areas then under Russian control (about 90,000 km2 or 15% of Ukraine's territory, roughly the size of Portugal) the annexation would still be the largest in Europe since World War II.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In other respects as well—in terms of the scale and intensity of hostilities, and the number of casualties—after the invasion, the war became the biggest war in Europe since World War II.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] From then through 2023, Russian offensives and Ukrainian counteroffensives gained only small amounts of territory.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The war has also led to attacks in Russia by Ukrainian and Ukrainian-backed forces, among them a cross-border offensive into Russia's Kursk region in August 2024.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Russia has repeatedly carried out deliberate and indiscriminate attacks on civilians far from the frontline.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The International Criminal Court (ICC) opened an investigation into war crimes and issued arrest warrants for Putin and several other Russian officials.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] The invasion received widespread international condemnation from governments and intergovernmental organisations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] On 2 March 2022 and on 23 February 2023, 141 member states of the UN General Assembly voted for a resolution saying that Russia should immediately withdraw.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Seven, including Russia, voted against the measure.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Political reactions to the invasion included new sanctions imposed on Russia, which triggered widespread economic effects on the Russian and world economies.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Sanctions forced Russia to reorient its oil exports to non-sanctioning countries such as India, rely more on LNG (which was not subject to European Union sanctions), and shift its coal exports from Europe to Asia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Most European countries cancelled nuclear cooperation with Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Over seventy sovereign states and the European Union delivered humanitarian aid to Ukraine, and nearly fifty countries plus the EU provided military aid.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Economic sanctions included a ban on Russian aircraft using EU airspace, a ban of certain Russian banks from the SWIFT international payments system, and a ban on certain Russian media outlets.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Reactions to the invasion have included public response, media responses, peace efforts, and the examination of the legal implications of the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Some countries, particularly in the Global South, saw public sympathy or outright support for Russia, due in part to distrust of US foreign policy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Protests and demonstrations were held worldwide, including some in Russia and parts of Ukraine occupied by Russia.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Calls for a boycott of Russian goods spread on social media platforms, while hackers attacked Russian websites, particularly those operated by the Russian government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] Anti-Russian sentiment against Russians living abroad surged after the invasion.
[src:absolute-monarchy/2022-russian-invasion-of-ukraine] In March 2022, Russian's parliament introduced prison sentences of up to 15 years for publishing "fake news" about Russian military operations, intended to suppress any criticism related to the war.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The **5 October 1910 Revolution** (Portuguese: *Revolução de 5 de outubro de 1910*) was the overthrow of the centuries-old Portuguese monarchy and its replacement by the First Portuguese Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] It was the result of a *coup d'état* organized by the Portuguese Republican Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The proponents of the republic, particularly the Republican Party, found ways to take advantage of the situation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The Republican Party presented itself as the only one with a programme capable of regaining Portugal's lost status and placing it on the path of progress.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After the reluctance of the military to oppose the nearly two thousand soldiers and sailors that rebelled on 3 and 4 October 1910, the Republic was proclaimed at 9 a.m the next day from the balcony of Lisbon's City Hall.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] A provisional government led by Teófilo Braga directed the fate of the country until the approval of the Constitution in 1911, which marked the beginning of the First Republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The national anthem and flag were changed, and some civil and religious liberties established; a wave of harsh anti-clericalism soon followed, corroding relations between the Republic and the Catholic Church.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The swift compliance by the government to the British demands was seen as a national humiliation by a broad cross-section of the population and the elite.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This exacerbated deep dissatisfaction with the new monarch, King Carlos I, the royal family and the institution of the monarchy, all of which were seen as responsible for the alleged process of "national decline".
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The republicans knew how to take advantage of the dissatisfaction, initiating an increase of their social support base that would climax in the demise of the regime.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On 14 January, the progressive government fell and the leader of the Regenerador Party, António de Serpa Pimentel, was chosen to form the new government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The progressivists then began to attack the king, voting for republican candidates in the March election of that year, questioning the colonial agreement then signed with the British.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On 1 April 1890, the explorer Silva Porto self-immolated wrapped in a Portuguese flag in Kuito, Angola, after failed negotiations with the locals, under orders of Paiva Couceiro, which he attributed to the *ultimatum*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The death of the well-known explorer of the African continent generated a wave of national sentiment, and his funeral was followed by a crowd in Porto.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On 11 April, Guerra Junqueiro's poetic work *Finis Patriae*, a satire criticizing the King, went on sale.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the city of Porto, on 31 January 1891, a military uprising against the monarchy took place, constituted mainly by sergeants and enlisted ranks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The movement was, shortly afterwards, suppressed by a military detachment of the municipal guard that remained loyal to the government, resulting in 40 injured and 12 casualties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] 250 received sentences of between 18 months and 15 years of exile in Africa.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Despite its failure, the rebellion of 31 January 1891 was the first large threat felt by the monarchic regime and a sign of what would come almost two decades later.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The revolutionary movement of 5 October 1910 occurred following the ideological and political action that, since its creation in 1876, the Portuguese Republican Party (PRP) had been developing with the objective of overthrowing the monarchic regime.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Disagreements within the party became more connected with matters of political than ideological strategy.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The ideological direction of the Portuguese republicanism had been traced much earlier by the works of José Félix Henriques Nogueira, little changed through the years, except in terms of later adaptation to the everyday realities of the country.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The works of Teófilo Braga contributed to this task by trying to concretize the decentralization and federalist ideas, abandoning the socialist quality in favour of democratic aspects.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This change also aimed to attract the small and medium bourgeoisie, which turned into one of the main bases of republican support.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the election of 13 October 1878 the PRP elected its first member of parliament, José Joaquim Rodrigues de Freitas, for Porto.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] There was also an intention to give the overthrow of the monarchy overtones of unification, nationalism and being above the particular interests of individual social classes.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This panacea that would cure, once and for all, all the ills of the nation, elevating it to glory, emphasized two fundamental tendencies: nationalism and colonialism.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] From this combination came the final desertion of Iberian Federalism, patent in the first republican theses by José Félix Henriques Nogueira, identifying the monarchy as antipatriotism and the yielding to foreign interests.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Ideological issues were not, ultimately, fundamental to the republican strategy: for the majority of sympathizers, who didn't even know the texts of the main manifestos, it was enough to be against the monarchy, against the Church and against the political corruption of traditional parties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, this lack of ideological preoccupation did not mean that the party did not bother to spread its principles.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The most effective action of dissemination was the propaganda made through its rallies and popular demonstrations and bulletins such as *A Voz Pública* (The Public Voice) in Porto, *O Século* (The Age, from 1880) *O Mundo* (The World, from 1900) and *A Luta* (The Struggle, from 1906) in Lisbon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The republican propaganda managed to take advantage of some historical facts with popular repercussions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The celebrations of the third centenary of the death of Luís de Camões (Portugal's Shakespeare) in 1580, and the British *ultimatum* in 1890, for example, were capitalized on to present the republicans as the true representatives of the purest national sentiments and popular aspirations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The third centenary of Camões was commemorated with great celebrations: a civic entourage that went through the streets of Lisbon, in the middle of great popular enthusiasm and, also, the transfer of the remains of Camões and Vasco da Gama to Jerónimos Monastery.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The atmosphere of the national celebration that characterized the commemorations complemented the patriotic exaltation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The idea of the Camões commemorations came from the Lisbon Geographic Society, but the execution was entrusted to a commission constituted by, amongst others, Teófilo Braga, Ramalho Ortigão, Jaime Batalha Reis, Magalhães Lima and Pinheiro Chagas, leading figures of the Republican Party.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] From this date to 1900 there was no republican parliamentary representation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In this phase, while separated from parliament, the party committed itself to its internal organization.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After a period of great repression of PRP, the republican movement could reenter the legislative race in 1900, electing four parliament members: Afonso Costa, Alexandre Braga, António José de Almeida and João de Meneses.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On 1 February 1908, while returning to Lisbon from the Ducal Palace in Vila Viçosa in Alentejo, where they had spent time hunting, the King Dom Carlos I and his eldest son and heir-apparent, Luís Filipe, Prince Royal of Portugal were assassinated in Lisbon's Commerce Square.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The attack occurred after a progressive decline of the Portuguese political system, effective since the Regeneration, due in part by the political erosion stemming from a system of rotating governments in which the Progressive and Regenerator Parties kept alternating in government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The king, as arbiter of the system under the Constitution, had designated João Franco as the president of the Council of Ministers (government chief).
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] João Franco, dissident of the Regenerator Party, convinced the king to dissolve the parliament so that he could implement a series of measures with an aim to moralize Portuguese politics.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This decision irritated not only republicans but the royalist opposition as well; led by political rivals of Franco who accused him of governing as a dictator.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The events were aggravated by the issues of the advanced payments to the Royal House and the signing of the decree of 30 January 1908 that foresaw the banishment to the colonies, without judgement, those involved in a failed republican coup two days prior.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The Royal Family was in the Ducal Palace of Vila Viçosa, but the events led the king to bring forward his return to Lisbon, taking a train from the station of Vila Viçosa on the morning of 1 February.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The royal escort arrived in Barreiro in the evening where, to cross the Tagus, it took a steam boat to Terreiro do Paço in Lisbon, at around 5pm.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Despite the atmosphere of great tension, the king chose to continue in an open carriage, with a reduced escort, to demonstrate normality.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] While greeting the crowds present in the square, the carriage was struck by several shots.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] One of the carbine bullets hit the king's neck, killing him immediately.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] More shots followed, fatally wounding the prince.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The queen defended herself with a bouquet of flowers offered by the people, which she used to hit one of the attackers who had climbed onto the carriage.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Two of the attackers, Manuel Buíça, a primary school teacher, and Alfredo Luís da Costa, a commerce employee and editor, were killed at the scene, others managed to escape.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The carriage entered the Navy Arsenal, where the deaths of the king and his heir were verified.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After the attack, João Franco's government was dismissed and a rigorous investigation was launched which found, two years later, that the attack had been committed by members of the secret organisation *Carbonária*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The investigation formally concluded on 5 October 1910.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, more suspects were subsequently found to have had direct involvement, some of whom went into hiding in Brazil and France, though at least two had been killed by the *Carbonária*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Europe was shocked by the attack, since King Carlos was highly regarded by other European heads of state.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The Lisbon regicide hastened the end of the monarchy by placing the young and inexperienced D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II on the throne and throwing the monarchical parties against one another.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Due to his young age (18 years) and the tragic and bloody way in which he reached power, Manuel II of Portugal obtained an initial sympathy from the public.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The young king began his rule by nominating a consensus government presided by admiral Francisco Joaquim Ferreira do Amaral.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This government of *pacification*, as it became known, despite achieving a temporary calm, only lasted for a short amount of time.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The political situation degraded again quickly, leading to having seven different governments in the space of two years.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The monarchical parties rose against each other once more and fragmented into splinter groups, while the Republican Party continued to gain ground.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the election of 5 April 1908, the last legislative elections to occur during the monarchy, seven members were elected to parliament, among which were Estêvão de Vasconcelos, Feio Terenas and Manuel de Brito Camacho.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the election of 28 August 1910 the party had a resounding success, electing 14 members to parliament, 10 for Lisbon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, in spite of the evident electoral success of the republican movement, the most revolutionary sector of the party called for armed struggle as the best means to achieve power in a short amount of time.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] It was this faction that came victorious from the party congress that took place in Setúbal between 23 and 25 April 1909.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The directorate, composed by the moderate Teófilo Braga, Basílio Teles, Eusébio Leão, José Cupertino Ribeiro and José Relvas, received from the congress the imperative mandate to *start the revolution*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The logistic role for the preparation of plot was assigned to the most radical elements.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The civil committee was formed by Afonso Costa, João Pinheiro Chagas and António José de Almeida, while the admiral Carlos Cândido dos Reis was the leader of the military committee.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] António José de Almeida was assigned the role of organising the secret societies such as the *Carbonária* – in whose leadership was integrated the naval commissary António Machado Santos —, the freemasons and the *Junta Liberal*, led by Miguel Bombarda.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This eminent doctor played an important part in the dissemination of republican propaganda among the bourgeoisie, which brought many sympathizers to the republican cause.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The period between the congress of 1909 and the emergence of the revolution was marked by great instability and political and social unrest, with several threats of uprising risking the revolution due to the impatience of the navy, led by Machado Santos, who was ready for action.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On 3 October 1910 the republican uprising foreshadowed by the political unrest finally took place.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the summer of 1910 Lisbon was teeming with rumours and many times the President of the Council of Ministers (Prime Minister) Teixeira de Sousa was warned of imminent *coups d'état*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The revolution was not an exception: the *coup* was expected by the government, who on 3 October gave orders for all the garrison troops of the city to be on guard.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II by Brazilian president Hermes da Fonseca, then on a state visit to Portugal, the monarch retreated to the Palace of Necessidades while his uncle and sworn heir to the throne, prince D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Afonso, went on to the Citadel of Cascais.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After the murder of Miguel Bombarda, shot by one of his patients, the republican leaders assembled with urgency on the night of the 3rd.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Some officials were against the meeting due to the strong military presence, but Admiral Cândido dos Reis insisted for it to take place, saying "*A Revolução não será adiada: sigam-me, se quiserem.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Havendo um só que cumpra o seu dever, esse único serei eu.*" ("The Revolution will not be delayed: follow me, if you want.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] If there is only one that fulfills their duty, this only one will be me.").
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Machado Santos had already got into action and did not attend the assembly.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Instead, he went to the military quarters of the 16th Infantry Regiment where a revolutionary corporal had triggered a rebellion involving the majority of the garrison.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] A commander and a captain were killed when they made an attempt to control it.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] With the arrival of Machado Santos two columns were formed which were placed under the leadership of captains Sá Cardoso and Palla.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The first went to meet the 2nd Infantry Regiment and the 2nd *Caçadores* Regiment, also sympathizers of the rebellion, to go on to Alcântara where it was to support the naval barracks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The original route intersected with a Municipal Guard outpost which forced the column to follow a different route.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After a few confrontations with the police and civilians, it finally found the column led by Palla.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Together, the columns advanced to Rotunda, where they entrenched at around 5am.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The stationed force was composed of around 200 to 300 men of the 1st Artillery Regiment, 50 to 60 men of the 16th Infantry Regiment and around 200 civilians.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The captains Sá Cardoso and Palla and the naval commissary Machado Santos were among the 9 officers in command.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Lieutenant Ladislau Parreira and some officers and civilians entered the barracks of the Naval Corps of Alcântara at 1am, managing to take arms, provoke a revolt and capture the commanders, one of whom was wounded.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The aim of this action was to prevent the exit of the cavalry unit of the Municipal Guard, an aim that was achieved.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] For this end, they required the support of 3 warships anchored in the Tagus.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] By this time, Lieutenant Mendes Cabeçadas had already taken command of the mutinied crew of the *NRP Adamastor* while the mutinied crew of the *São Rafael* waited for an officer to command it.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] At about 7am Ladislau Parreira, having been informed by civilians of the situation, sent the Second-Lieutenant Tito de Morais to take command of the *São Rafael*, with orders for both ships to support the garrison of the barracks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] When it became known that on the ship *D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Carlos I* the crew had begun a mutiny but the officers had entrenched, Lieutenant Carlos da Maia and a few sailors left the *São Rafael*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After some gunfire from which a lieutenant and a ship commander were wounded, the officers gave up control of the *D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Carlos I*, yielding it to the hands of the republicans.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] That was the last unit to join the rebels, which included by then part of the 1st Artillery Regiment, 16th Infantry Regiment, the naval corps and the three warships.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Navy members had joined in large numbers as expected, but many military sections considered sympathizers with the cause hadn't joined.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Even so, the republican forces included about 400 men in Rotunda, 1000 to 1500 in Alcântara counting the naval crews, as well as having managed to take hold of the city's artillery, with most of the ammunition, to which was added the naval artillery.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Rotunda and Alcântara were occupied, but concrete plans for the revolution had not yet been decided and the main leaders hadn't yet appeared.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In spite of this, the beginning of the events did not occur favorably for the rebels.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The three cannon shots – the accorded signal for the civilians and military to advance – did not take place.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Only a shot was heard and the Admiral Cândido dos Reis, expecting the signal to take command of the warships, was informed that everything had failed, which prompted him to retire to his sister's house.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The next morning his dead body was found in Arroios.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In desperation, he had committed suicide by a shot to the head.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, in Rotunda, the apparent calm in the city was so discouraging to the rebels that officers preferred to give up.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Sá Cardoso, Palla and other officers retired to their houses, but Machado Santos stayed and assumed command.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This decision proved fundamental to the success of the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The military garrison of Lisbon was composed by four infantry regiments, two cavalry regiments and two *Caçadores* (light infantry) battalions, with a theoretical total of 6982 men.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, in practice, there were other useful units in military outposts used for lookout and general police duties, especially in the industrial district of Barreiro due to the bout of strikes and syndicalist activity that had been ongoing since September.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Ever since the previous year the government forces had a plan of action, drawn up by order of the military commander of Lisbon, General Manuel Rafael Gorjão Henriques.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] When, on the evening of the 3rd, the President of the Council of Ministers Teixeira de Sousa informed him of the imminence of a revolt, a prevention order was soon sent to the garrisons in the city.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The units of Artillery 3 and Light Infantry 6 were called from Santarém, while Infantry 15 was called from Tomar.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Little is known of the Fiscal Guard (a total of 1397 men), only that a few soldiers were with the troops in Rossio.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The civil police (total of 1200 men) stayed in their barracks.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This inaction decreased the effective government forces by approximately 2600 men.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] As soon as news of the concentration of rebels in Rotunda were received, the military command of the city organized a detachment to break them up.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The column, under the command of Colonel Alfredo Albuquerque, was formed by units that had been removed from the protection of the Palace of Necessidades: 2nd Infantry, 2nd Cavalry and the mobile battery of Queluz.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The latter included the colonial war hero Henrique Mitchell de Paiva Couceiro.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The column advanced until near the prison, where it assumed combat positions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, before these were completed, the column was attacked by rebels.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The attack was repelled but resulted in a few wounded men, several dead pack animals and the scattering of about half the infantry.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Paiva Couceiro responded with cannons and the infantry that remained during 45 minutes, ordering an attack that was carried out by around 30 soldiers, but which was beaten with some casualties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Continuing the gunfire, he ordered a new attack, but only 20 soldiers followed the order.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Thinking that he had found the right time to assault the barracks of Artillery 1, Paiva Couceiro requested reinforcement to the division's command.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, he received the perplexing order to retreat.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, a column had been formed with the intention to attack simultaneously the rebels in Rotunda, a plan that was never carried out because of the order to retreat.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The column reached Rossio in the evening without having joined combat.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This inaction was not caused by the incompetence of its commander, General António Carvalhal, as would become clear the next day, when he was named chief of the Military Division for the republican government: he had changed sides.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Reinforcements from other parts of the country, expected by the government throughout 4 October, never arrived.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Only the units already mentioned and called for the preventive measures received orders to advance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Since the beginning of the revolution, members of the *Carbonária* had disconnected the telegraph lines, thus cutting communication with units outside Lisbon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In addition, the rebels had cut off the railway tracks, which meant that even if the troops followed the orders to advance on Lisbon, they would never arrive on time.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Reinforcements from the Setúbal peninsula were also unlikely to arrive, since the Tagus river was controlled by rebel ships.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] This attack undermined the morale of the pro-government forces in Rossio.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After the dinner with Hermes da Fonseca, D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II had returned to the Palace of Necessidades, keeping the company of a few officers.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] They were playing bridge when the rebels began an attack on the building.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The king attempted some phone calls but, finding that the lines had been cut, managed only to inform the Queen Mother, who was in Pena National Palace, about the situation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Soon afterwards, groups of units that were loyal to the king arrived at the scene and managed to defeat the attacks of the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] At 9 o'clock the king received a phone call from the president of the council, advising him to find refuge in Mafra or Sintra, since the rebels were threatening to bomb the Palace of Necessidades.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] D.Manuel II refused to leave, saying to those present: "Go if you want, I'm staying.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] With the arrival of the mobile battery from Queluz, the pieces were arranged in the palace gardens so that they could bombard the quarters of the revolutionary sailors, which were located at no more than 100 metres from the palace.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] However, before they had time to start, the commander of the battery received the order to cancel the bombing and join the forces that were leaving the palace, integrated into the column that would attack the rebel forces of the 1st Artillery in the Rotunda.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] At around midday the cruisers *Adamastor* and *São Rafael*, which had anchored in front of the sailors' quarters, started the bombardment of the Palace of Necessidades, an action which served to demoralize the present monarchical forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The king took refuge in a small house in the palace's park, where he could ring Teixeira de Sousa, since the revolutionaries had only cut the special state telephone lines and not the general network.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The king ordered the prime minister to send the battery from Queluz to the palace to prevent a naval landing, but the prime minister replied that the main action was happening in Rotunda and all the troops that were there were needed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Taking into account that the available troops were not sufficient to defeat the rebels in Rotunda, the prime minister made it obvious to the king that it would be more convenient to retire to Sintra or Mafra so that the stationed forces of the palace could reinforce the troops in Rotunda.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II and his advisors set out to Mafra, where the Infantry School would provide enough forces to protect the monarch.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] While approaching Benfica the king dismissed the municipal guard squad that escorted him so that they could join the fight against the rebels.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the meantime, Counsellor João de Azevedo Coutinho arrived and advised the king to call to Mafra the queens D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Maria Pia (respectively, the king's mother and grandmother), who were in the palaces of Pena and Vila in Sintra, and to prepare to continue on to Porto, where they would organize a resistance.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In Lisbon, the king's departure did not bring a large advantage to the government since the majority of the troops now available to engage the rebel forces did not follow the orders to march to Rossio Square to prevent the concentration of rebel artillery in Alcântara.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] On the night of 4 October morale was low amongst the monarchical troops stationed in Rossio Square, due to the constant danger of being bombarded by the naval forces and not even Couceiro's batteries, strategically placed there, could bring them comfort.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the headquarters there were discussions about the best position to bomb the Rotunda.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] At 3am, Paiva Couceiro departed with a mobile battery, escorted by a municipal guard squad, and positioned himself in Castro Guimarães Garden, in Torel, waiting for daybreak.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] When the forces in Rotunda began to fire on Rossio, revealing their position, Paiva Couceiro opened fire, causing casualties and sowing confusion amongst the rebels.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The bombardment continued with advantage towards the monarchical side, but at eight in the morning Paiva Couceiro received orders to stop fighting, as there would be an armistice of an hour.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, in Rossio, after Paiva Couceiro's departure with the battery, the morale of the monarchical troops, which considered themselves helpless, deteriorated even more due to the threats of bombardment by the naval forces.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Infantry 5 and some members of Light Infantry 5 insisted that they would not oppose a naval landing.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Confronted with this fraternization with the enemy, the commanders of these formations went to the headquarters, where they were surprised with the news of the armistice.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The new German representative, who had arrived two days earlier, had taken rooms in Hotel Avenida Palace, which housed many foreigners.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The proximity of the building to the combat zone represented a great danger which prompted the diplomat to intervene.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] He addressed himself to the General Gorjão Henriques to request a cease-fire that would enable him to evacuate foreign citizens.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Without notifying the government, and perhaps hoping to buy time for the arrival of the reinforcements, the general agreed.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The German diplomat, accompanied by a man with a white flag, went to the Rotunda to discuss the armistice with the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The latter, however, at the sight of the white flag, mistakenly thought that the king's forces were surrendering, prompting them to join with crowds a celebration of the new republic.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the square, Machado Santos initially refused to accept the armistice, but eventually accepted it after the insistence of the diplomat.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Then, seeing the massive popular support for the revolution in the streets, he recklessly went to the headquarters, accompanied by many of the people and several officers who left the position in the Rotunda.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The situation in Rossio, with the pouring of the populace onto the streets, was very confusing but advantageous to the republicans, given the obvious public support.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Machado Santos spoke to General Gorjão Henriques and invited him to keep the role of division commander, but he refused.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] António Carvalhal, known to be a republican sympathiser, then received command.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Soon afterwards, at 9 o'clock in the morning, the Republic was proclaimed by José Relvas from the balcony of the Lisbon City Hall.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] A provisional government was then nominated, presided by members of the Portuguese Republican Party, with the mandate to govern the nation until a new constitution was approved.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The revolution caused dozens of casualties.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The exact number is unknown, but it is recognized that as of 6 October 37 people killed in the revolution were registered in the morgue.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Several injured turned up at the hospitals, some of whom later died.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] For example, out of 78 injured victims checked into Hospital de São José, 14 died in the following days.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In Mafra, on the morning of 5 October, the king was looking for a way to reach Porto, an action that would be very difficult to carry out due to the almost non-existence of an escort and the innumerable revolutionary hubs spread throughout the country.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] At around midday the President of the Municipal Chamber of Mafra received a message from the new civil governor ordering the switching to a republican flag.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Soon afterwards the commander of the Infantry School also received a telegram from his new commander informing him of the current political situation.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The position of the royal family was becoming unsustainable.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The solution appeared when news arrived that the royal yacht *Amélia* had anchored nearby, in Ericeira.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] By 2am the yacht had collected from Cascais Citadel the king's uncle and heir to the throne, D.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Afonso, and knowing that the king was in Mafra, had moved to Ericeira, as it was the closest anchorage.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II, knowing that with the proclamation of the Republic he would be imprisoned, decided to go to Porto.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The royal family and some company departed for Ericeira where, by means of two fishing ships and in the presence of curious civilians, they embarked on the royal yacht.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] After ensuring that the letter would reach its destination, the king announced that he wanted to go to Porto.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] He met with an advisory council, the officers on board and part of the escort.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] *Amélia's* Captain João Agnelo Velez Caldeira Castelo Branco and Chief Officer João Jorge Moreira de Sá opposed this idea, claiming if Porto turned them away, they would not have enough fuel to reach a different anchorage.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Despite the king's insistence, the Chief Officer argued that they carried on board the whole royal family, so his main duty was to protect their lives.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] In the end, the chosen port was Gibraltar.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Upon arrival, the king received word Porto had also joined the republican cause.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] Manuel II ordered that the *Amélia*, as Portuguese State property, be returned to Lisbon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p01] The deposed king would live out the rest of his life in exile.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Provisional Government was constituted immediately: Presidency, Dr Joaquim Teófilo Braga.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Navy, Amaro Justiniano de Azevedo Gomes.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] By decree on 8 October, the Provisional Government determined the new names of the ministries, with the most important changes being made to the ministries of *the Kingdom*, *Treasure* and *Public Works*, which were renamed ministries of *Interior*, *Finances* and *Development*.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] However, Basílio Teles refused the position and, on the 12th, it was given to José Relvas.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] On 22 November, Brito Camacho entered government after the departure of António Luís Gomes, appointed Portuguese ambassador in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] During its time of power, the Provisional Government took a series of important measures that had long-lasting effects.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] To calm tempers and make reparations with the victims of the monarchy, a broad amnesty was granted for crimes against the security of the State, against religion, of disobedience, of forbidden weaponry usage, etc.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Catholic Church resented the measures taken by the Provisional Government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Provisional Government also opted for the dissolution of the then municipal guards of Lisbon and Porto, creating instead a new public body of defense an order, the National Republican Guard.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] For the colonies, new legislation was created in order to grant autonomy to overseas territories, an essential condition for their development.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The national symbols were modified — the flag and the national anthem, a new monetary unit was adopted — the *escudo*, equivalent to a thousand *réis*, and even the Portuguese orthography was simplified and appropriately regulated through the Orthographic Reform of 1911.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Provisional Government enjoyed extensive power until the opening of the National Constituent Assembly on 19 June 1911, following the election of 28 May of the same year.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] At that time, the president of the Provisional Government, Teófilo Braga, handed over to the Constituent Assembly the powers he had received on 5 October 1910.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Nevertheless, the Assembly approved with acclaim the proposal presented by their president, Anselmo Braamcamp Freire to the congress: "The National Constituent Assembly confirms, until future deliberation, the functions of the Executive Power to the Provisional Government of the Republic".
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] With the establishment of the Republic, the national symbols were modified.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] By a Provisional Government decree dated 15 October 1910, a committee was appointed to design the new symbols.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] In relation to the flag, there were two inclinations: one of keeping the blue and white colors, traditional of Portuguese flags, and another of using "more republican" colours: green and red.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The committee's proposal suffered several alterations, with the final design being rectangular, with the first two-fifths closest to the flagpole to be green, and the three remaining fifths, red.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Green was chosen because it was considered the "color of hope", while red was chosen as a "combative, hot, virile" color.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The project of the flag was approved by the Provisional Government by vote on 19 November 1910.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] On 1 December was celebrated the Feast of the Flag in front of the Municipal Chamber of Lisbon.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Constituent Assembly promulgated the adoption of the flag on 19 June 1911.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] On 19 June 1911 the National Constitutional Assembly proclaimed *A Portuguesa* as the national anthem, replacing the old anthem *Hymno da Carta* in use since May 1834, and its status as national symbol was included in the new constitution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] *A Portuguesa* was composed in 1890, with music by Alfredo Keil and lyrics by Henrique Lopes de Mendonça, in response to the 1890 British Ultimatum.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Because of its patriotic character, it had been used, with slight modifications, by the rebels of the 1891 uprising in a failed attempt at a *coup d'état* to establish a republic in Portugal, an event which caused the anthem to be forbidden by the monarchic authorities.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The anthem was later modified; the official version used today in national civil and military ceremonies and during visits of foreign heads of state was approved on 4 September 1957.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Two versions of the bust on coins from the Portuguese Republic: by Francisco dos Santos, above; by José Simões de Almeida, below.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The official bust of the Republic was chosen through a national competition promoted by Lisbon's city council in 1911, in which nine sculptors participated.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The winning entry was that of Francisco dos Santos and is currently displayed in the Municipal Chamber.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The original piece is found in Casa Pia, an institution from which the sculptor was alumnus.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] There is another bust that was adopted as the face of the Republic, designed by José Simões de Almeida (sobrinho) in 1908.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The original is found in the Municipal Chamber of Figueiró dos Vinhos.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The model for this bust was Ilda Pulga, a young shop employee from Chiado.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The bust shows Republic wearing a Phrygian cap, influence of the French Revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Simões' bust was soon adopted by Freemasonry and used in the funerals of Miguel Bombarda and Cândido dos Reis, but when the final contest took place, despite its relative popularity, it was second place to the bust by Francisco dos Santos.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Republican leaders adopted a severe and highly controversial policy of anti-clericalism.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] At home, the policy polarized society and lost the republic potential supporters, and abroad it offended American and European states which had their citizens engaged in religious work there, adding substantially to the republic's bad press.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The revolution and the republic which it spawned were essentially anticlerical and had a "hostile" approach to the issue of church and state separation, like that of the French Revolution, the Spanish Constitution of 1931 and the Mexican Constitution of 1917.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Secularism began to be discussed in Portugal back in the 19th century, during the Casino Conferences in 1871, promoted by Antero de Quental.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The republican movement associated the Catholic Church with the monarchy, and opposed its influence in Portuguese society.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The secularization of the Republic constituted one of the main actions to be taken in the political agenda of the Portuguese Republican Party and the Freemasonry.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Monarchists in a last-ditch effort sought to outflank the republicans by enacting anticlerical measures of their own, even enacting a severe restriction on the Jesuits on the day before the revolution.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Soon after the establishment of the Republic, on 8 October 1910, Minister for Justice Afonso Costa reinstated Marquess of Pombal's laws against the Jesuits, and Joaquim António de Aguiar's laws in relation to religious orders.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Church's property and assets were expropriated by the State.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The religious oath and other religious elements found in the statutes of the University of Coimbra were abolished, and matriculations into first year of the Theology Faculty were cancelled, as were places in the Canon law course, suppressing the teaching of Christian doctrine.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Religious holidays turned into working days, keeping however the Sunday as a resting day for labor reasons.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] As well as that, the Armed forces were forbidden from participating in religious solemn events.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Bishops were persecuted, expelled or suspended from their activities in the course of the secularization.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] All but one were driven from their dioceses. the property of clerics was seized by the state, wearing of the cassock was banned, all minor seminaries were closed and all but five major seminaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] A law of 22 February 1918 permitted only two seminaries in the country, but they had not been given their property back.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Religious orders were expelled from the country, including 31 orders comprising members in 164 houses (in 1917 some orders were permitted to form again).
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Religious education was prohibited in both primary and secondary school.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] In response to the several anticlerical decrees, Portuguese bishops launched a collective pastoral defending the Church's doctrine, but its reading was prohibited by the government.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] In spite of this, some prelates continued to publicize the text, among which was the bishop of Porto, António Barroso.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] This resulted in him being called to Lisbon by Afonso Costa, where he was stripped from his ecclesiastic functions.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The secularization peaked with the *Law of Separation of the State and the Church* on 20 April 1911, with a large acceptance by the revolutionaries.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The law was only promulgated by the Assembly in 1914, but its implementation was immediate after the publishing of the decree.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The Portuguese Church tried to respond, classifying the law as "injustice, oppression, spoliation and mockery", but without success.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] Afonso Costa even predicted the eradication of Catholicism in the space of three generations.
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] The application of the law began on 1 July 1911, with the creation of a "Central Commission".
[src:absolute-monarchy/5-october-1910-revolution-p02] As one commentator put it, "ultimately the Church was to survive the official vendetta against organized religion".
